0002341c    ret_code_t app_button_init(uint8_t max_buttons, void* p_buffer)

0002341c  // Initialize button handler module
0002341c  // SDK: components/libraries/button/app_button.c
0002341c  // 
0002341c  // Initializes button detection and debouncing system.
0002341c  // 
0002341c  // Parameters:
0002341c  // - p_buttons: Array of app_button_cfg_t structures
0002341c  // - button_count: Number of buttons to monitor
0002341c  // - detection_delay: Debounce delay in milliseconds
0002341c  // 
0002341c  // Button configuration (app_button_cfg_t):
0002341c  // - pin_no: GPIO pin number (0-31)
0002341c  // - active_state: APP_BUTTON_ACTIVE_LOW (0) or APP_BUTTON_ACTIVE_HIGH
0002341c  // (1)
0002341c  // - pull_cfg: NRF_GPIO_PIN_PULLUP, PULLDOWN, or NOPULL
0002341c  // - button_handler: Callback function on button press/release
0002341c  // 
0002341c  // Typical button configuration:
0002341c  // - Button 0 (P0.11): Mode/power button
0002341c  // - Button 1 (P0.12): Up/increase button
0002341c  // - Button 2 (P0.13): Down/decrease button
0002341c  // 
0002341c  // Debouncing mechanism:
0002341c  // 1. GPIOTE detects edge (rising or falling)
0002341c  // 2. Start app_timer with detection_delay (typically 50ms)
0002341c  // 3. On timer expiry: Read pin state again
0002341c  // 4. If state stable: Call button_handler with event
0002341c  // 5. If state changed: Ignore as bounce
0002341c  // 
0002341c  // Button events:
0002341c  // - APP_BUTTON_PUSH: Button pressed (active state detected)
0002341c  // - APP_BUTTON_RELEASE: Button released (inactive state detected)
0002341c  // 
0002341c  // Initialization process:
0002341c  // 1. Configure GPIOs with pull resistors
0002341c  // 2. Register GPIOTE handlers via app_gpiote_user_register()
0002341c  // 3. Enable GPIOTE sensing on configured pins
0002341c  // 4. Store button table at data_20004100
0002341c  // 
0002341c  // Returns: 0 on success, NRF_ERROR_INVALID_PARAM if invalid config
0002341c  10b5       push    {r4, lr}
0002341e  82b0       sub     sp, #8
00023420  164b       ldr     r3, [pc, #0x58]
00023422  93f85440   ldrb    r4, [r3, #0x54]
00023426  34bb       cbnz    r4, #0x23476

00023428  2346       mov     r3, r4
0002342a  06e0       b       #0x2343a

0002342c  134a       ldr     r2, [pc, #0x4c]
0002342e  1a44       add     r2, r3
00023430  ff21       movs    r1, #0xff
00023432  82f83010   strb    r1, [r2, #0x30]
00023436  0133       adds    r3, #1
00023438  dbb2       uxtb    r3, r3

0002343a  1f2b       cmp     r3, #0x1f
0002343c  f6d9       bls     #0x2342c

0002343e  04e0       b       #0x2344a

00023440  2046       mov     r0, r4
00023442  fff7dbff   bl      #0x233fc
00023446  0134       adds    r4, #1
00023448  e4b2       uxtb    r4, r4

0002344a  0b2c       cmp     r4, #0xb
0002344c  f8d9       bls     #0x23440

0002344e  0721       movs    r1, #7
00023450  0620       movs    r0, #6
00023452  00f077fa   bl      #0x23944
00023456  0a4b       ldr     r3, [pc, #0x28]

000234e8    int32_t gpiote_channel_init(int32_t arg1, char* arg2, int32_t arg3)

000234e8  // Initialize GPIOTE channel for GPIO event detection
000234e8  // arg1: GPIO pin number
000234e8  // arg2: Config structure (polarity, pull, event type)
000234e8  // arg3: Callback function pointer
000234e8  // Returns 0 on success, 4 if no slots available, 8 if already
000234e8  // initialized
000234e8  // Allocates timer slot via timer_slot_allocate()
000234e8  // Configures pin mode and pull resistors based on arg2[1] and arg2[2]
000234e8  // If arg2[2]==0 (PORT event): Sets PORT event bit in 0x20003588
000234e8  // If arg2[2]!=0 (GPIOTE event): Configures GPIOTE.CONFIG register
000234e8  // with pin, polarity, event mode

00023734    int32_t GPIOTE_IRQHandler()

00023734  // GPIOTE interrupt handler - processes GPIO and PORT events
00023734  // Scans GPIOTE channels 0-7 for triggered events
00023734  // - Checks GPIOTE.EVENTS_IN[0-7] and GPIOTE.INTENSET mask
00023734  // - Clears event registers, accumulates bitmask in r5
00023734  // Handles PORT event (GPIOTE.EVENTS_PORT):
00023734  // - Sets bit 31 in r5 if PORT event triggered
00023734  // - Reads P0.IN state into var_1c array
00023734  // For GPIOTE events (bits 0-7):
00023734  // - Extracts pin number and polarity from GPIOTE.CONFIG[channel]
00023734  // - Calls registered callback from data_20003540 array
00023734  // For PORT events (bit 31):
00023734  // - Reads P0.IN into multiple snapshots (var_18, var_28)
00023734  // - Processes port state change callbacks from data_20003590 array
00023734  // - Implements debouncing by comparing multiple P0.IN reads
00023734  // - Updates PIN_CNF polarity based on detected edge
00023734  // Critical interrupt handler for all GPIO-based peripherals
00023734  // SDK: components/drivers_nrf/gpiote/nrf_drv_gpiote.c
00023734  f0b5       push    {r4, r5, r6, r7, lr} {var_4} {__saved_r7} {__saved_r6} {__saved_r5} {__saved_r4}

00023944    void nvic_set_priority_and_enable(uint32_t arg1, int32_t arg2)

00023944  // Set NVIC interrupt priority and enable interrupt
00023944  // arg1: IRQ number (can be negative for system exceptions)
00023944  // arg2: Priority value (0-255, shifted left 5 bits for register)
00023944  // 
00023944  // If arg1 < 0 (system exception):
00023944  // - Sets priority in System Handler Priority Register at 0xe000ed14
00023944  // - Offset calculated as (arg1 & 0xf)
00023944  // 
00023944  // If arg1 >= 0 (peripheral interrupt):
00023944  // - Sets priority in NVIC IPR at base 0x1fff1c00
00023944  // - Enables interrupt in NVIC ISER at 0xe000e100
00023944  // - Uses bit position (arg1 & 0x1f) in word (arg1 >> 5)
00023944  // 
00023944  // Critical for configuring all peripheral interrupts (UART, GPIOTE,
00023944  // SAADC, etc.)
00023944  // Standard ARM Cortex-M4 NVIC configuration
00023944  // SDK: CMSIS core_cm4.h
00023944  0028       cmp     r0, #0
00023946  1ddb       blt     #0x23984

00023948  4901       lsls    r1, r1, #5
0002394a  c9b2       uxtb    r1, r1
0002394c  00f16043   add     r3, r0, #0xe0000000
00023950  03f56143   add     r3, r3, #0xe100
00023954  83f80013   strb    r1, [r3, #0x300]

00023958  0028       cmp     r0, #0
0002395a  08db       blt     #0x2396e

0002395c  00f01f01   and     r1, r0, #0x1f
00023960  4309       lsrs    r3, r0, #5
00023962  0122       movs    r2, #1
00023964  8a40       lsls    r2, r1
00023966  6033       adds    r3, #0x60
00023968  0a49       ldr     r1, [pc, #0x28]  {data_23994}  {0xe000e100}
0002396a  41f82320   str     r2, [r1, r3, lsl #2]

000239fa    int32_t* slist_pop_head(int32_t* arg1)

000239fa  // updates *arg1 = head->next, returns old head. Returns null if list
000239fa  // empty.

00023a34    int32_t clock_init()

00023a34  // Initialize clock control driver
00023a34  // SDK: components/drivers_nrf/clock/nrf_drv_clock.c
00023a34  // 
00023a34  // Initializes clock management for HFCLK and LFCLK.
00023a34  // 
00023a34  // Clock sources:
00023a34  // - HFCLK (High Frequency Clock, 64 MHz):
00023a34  //   * HFCLK_RC: Internal RC oscillator (default on reset)
00023a34  //   * HFCLK_XTAL: External 64 MHz crystal (accurate, required for
00023a34  // BLE)
00023a34  // - LFCLK (Low Frequency Clock, 32.768 kHz):
00023a34  //   * LFCLK_RC: Internal RC oscillator (250 ppm, low accuracy)
00023a34  //   * LFCLK_XTAL: External 32.768 kHz crystal (20 ppm, for timers)
00023a34  //   * LFCLK_SYNTH: Synthesized from HFCLK (power hungry)
00023a34  // 
00023a34  // CLOCK peripheral (base 0x40000000):
00023a34  // - TASKS_HFCLKSTART: Start HFCLK crystal
00023a34  // - TASKS_HFCLKSTOP: Stop HFCLK crystal (RC takes over)
00023a34  // - TASKS_LFCLKSTART: Start LFCLK crystal
00023a34  // - TASKS_LFCLKSTOP: Stop LFCLK crystal
00023a34  // - EVENTS_HFCLKSTARTED: HFCLK crystal running
00023a34  // - EVENTS_LFCLKSTARTED: LFCLK crystal running
00023a34  // - HFCLKSTAT: HFCLK source and state
00023a34  // - LFCLKSTAT: LFCLK source and state
00023a34  // 
00023a34  // Initialization sequence:
00023a34  // 1. Configure LFCLK source (XTAL for accuracy)
00023a34  // 2. Request LFCLK start via clock_lfclk_request()
00023a34  // 3. Register event handler for LFCLKSTARTED event
00023a34  // 4. Enable POWER_CLOCK_IRQHandler (NVIC IRQ 0)
00023a34  // 5. Wait for LFCLK to stabilize (~250ms for crystal)
00023a34  // 
00023a34  // HFCLK management:
00023a34  // - SoftDevice controls HFCLK for BLE radio
00023a34  // - Application typically doesn't need to manage HFCLK
00023a34  // - HFCLK auto-started by SoftDevice during BLE operations
00023a34  // 
00023a34  // LFCLK usage:
00023a34  // - RTC0: Reserved for SoftDevice
00023a34  // - RTC1: app_timer system
00023a34  // - RTC2: Real-time clock (Unix time)
00023a34  // - WDT: Watchdog timer
00023a34  // 
00023a34  // Called from: init_routine() before SoftDevice enable
00023a34  // Returns: 0 on success
00023a34  08b5       push    {r3, lr}
00023a36  114b       ldr     r3, [pc, #0x44]
00023a38  1b78       ldrb    r3, [r3]
00023a3a  0bb1       cbz     r3, #0x23a40

00023a3c  8520       movs    r0, #0x85

00023a3e  08bd       pop     {r3, pc}

00023a40  0e4b       ldr     r3, [pc, #0x38]
00023a42  0022       movs    r2, #0
00023a44  // g_event_scheduler_head @ 0x200035a0: Initialize event scheduler
00023a44  // list head to NULL
00023a44  9a60       str     r2, [r3, #8]
00023a46  // g_clock_state_1 @ 0x2000359c: Initialize clock module state to 0
00023a46  5a60       str     r2, [r3, #4]
00023a48  // g_clock_state_2 @ 0x200035a8: Initialize clock module state to 0
00023a48  1a61       str     r2, [r3, #0x10]
00023a4a  // g_clock_state_3 @ 0x200035a4: Initialize clock module state to 0
00023a4a  da60       str     r2, [r3, #0xc]
00023a4c  0c4b       ldr     r3, [pc, #0x30]
00023a4e  1b68       ldr     r3, [r3]
00023a50  13f0010f   tst     r3, #1
00023a54  0cd0       beq     #0x23a70

00023a5c  4ff08043   mov     r3, #0x40000000

00023a68  0122       movs    r2, #1

00023a80  int32_t data_23a80 = -0x1fff1f00

00023a84    int32_t clock_lfclk_request(int32_t* arg1)

00023a84  // Request LFCLK start
00023a84  // SDK: components/drivers_nrf/clock/nrf_drv_clock.c
00023a84  // 
00023a84  // Requests Low Frequency Clock to start.
00023a84  // 
00023a84  // LFCLK request handling:
00023a84  // 1. Increment request counter at data_20004200
00023a84  // 2. If first request (counter was 0):
00023a84  //    - Trigger CLOCK->TASKS_LFCLKSTART
00023a84  //    - Start crystal oscillator
00023a84  // 3. If already requested (counter > 0):
00023a84  //    - Just increment counter (already running)
00023a84  // 
00023a84  // Request counter allows multiple modules to independently
00023a84  // request LFCLK without interfering:
00023a84  // - RTC1 (app_timer): Requests on app_timer_init()
00023a84  // - RTC2 (real-time clock): Requests on rtc_init()
00023a84  // - SoftDevice: May request internally
00023a84  // 
00023a84  // LFCLK startup time:
00023a84  // - RC oscillator: ~250 s (fast, inaccurate)
00023a84  // - External crystal: ~250-500 ms (slow, accurate)
00023a84  // 
00023a84  // Startup event: CLOCK->EVENTS_LFCLKSTARTED
00023a84  // - Handled by POWER_CLOCK_IRQHandler
00023a84  // - Dispatches to clock_event_handler()
00023a84  // - Calls registered callbacks
00023a84  // 
00023a84  // Typical usage:
00023a84  // ```c
00023a84  // clock_init();  // Initialize clock driver
00023a84  // clock_lfclk_request();  // Request LFCLK start
00023a84  // // Wait for EVENTS_LFCLKSTARTED event
00023a84  // // Now safe to use RTC peripherals
00023a84  // ```
00023a84  // 
00023a84  // Must be paired with clock_lfclk_release() when done.
00023a84  // 
00023a84  // Returns: void
00023a84  10b5       push    {r4, lr} {var_4} {__saved_r4}
00023a86  82b0       sub     sp, #8
00023a88  0446       mov     r4, r0
00023a8a  194b       ldr     r3, [pc, #0x64]  {ptr_g_clock_initialized}  {g_clock_initialized}
00023a8c  9b78       ldrb    r3, [r3, #2]  {data_2000359a}
00023a8e  a3b1       cbz     r3, #0x23aba

00023a90  10b1       cbz     r0, #0x23a98

00023c44    void SAADC_IRQHandler()

00023c44  // SAADC interrupt handler - processes ADC conversion events
00023c44  // Handles multiple event types:
00023c44  // 
00023c44  // 1. EVENTS_END (conversion complete):
00023c44  //    - Clears event register
00023c44  //    - Prepares event structure: type=0, buffer info
00023c44  //    - Swaps buffer pointers at data_200035b0/b4/b8/c4/c6
00023c44  //    - Calls callback at data_200035ac with event data
00023c44  //    - Starts next conversion via TASKS_START if buffer available
00023c44  //    - Clears data_200035db flag
00023c44  // 
00023c44  // 2. EVENTS_STARTED (low power mode):
00023c44  //    - Clears event register
00023c44  //    - Configures RESULT_PTR and RESULT_MAXCNT based on buffer size
00023c44  //    - Handles partial buffer fills via data_200035c6 counter
00023c44  //    - Triggers TASKS_SAMPLE to start sampling
00023c44  //    - Sets data_200035db=1 when buffer exhausted
00023c44  // 
00023c44  // 3. EVENTS_CALIBRATEDONE (calibration complete):
00023c44  //    - Clears event register
00023c44  //    - Clears busy flag data_200035bc=0
00023c44  //    - Calls callback with type=2 event
00023c44  // 
00023c44  // 4. EVENTS_STOPPED (ADC stopped):
00023c44  //    - Clears event register
00023c44  //    - Clears busy flag data_200035bc=0
00023c44  // 
00023c44  // 5. Channel limit events (bits in data_200035c0):
00023c44  //    - Uses __clz to find triggered channel
00023c44  //    - Clears event register at offset 0x46+channel*4
00023c44  //    - Calls callback with type=1, channel, limit_type
00023c44  // 
00023c44  // Critical for ADC data acquisition and battery monitoring
00023c44  // SDK: components/drivers_nrf/saadc/nrf_drv_saadc.c
00023c44  10b5       push    {r4, lr} {var_4} {__saved_r4}
00023c46  88b0       sub     sp, #0x20
00023c48  684b       ldr     r3, [pc, #0x1a0]  {data_23dec}  {SAADC}
00023c4a  d3f80431   ldr     r3, [r3, #0x104]  {SAADC.EVENTS_END}
00023c4e  002b       cmp     r3, #0
00023c50  2cd0       beq     #0x23cac

00023c52  664b       ldr     r3, [pc, #0x198]  {data_23dec}  {SAADC}
00023c54  0022       movs    r2, #0
00023c56  c3f80421   str     r2, [r3, #0x104]  {0x0}  {SAADC.EVENTS_END}
00023c5a  d3f80431   ldr     r3, [r3, #0x104]  {SAADC.EVENTS_END}
00023c5e  0093       str     r3, [sp] {EVENTS_END}

00023df4    int32_t saadc_init(char* arg1, int32_t arg2)

00023df4  // Initialize SAADC (Successive Approximation ADC) peripheral
00023df4  // arg1: Config structure pointer (uses default at data_section_start
00023df4  // if NULL)
00023df4  // arg2: Event handler callback
00023df4  // Returns 8 if already initialized (data_200035d8==1)
00023df4  // Returns 7 if no callback provided (arg2==0)
00023df4  // 
00023df4  // Configuration sequence:
00023df4  // 1. Stores callback at data_200035ac
00023df4  // 2. Configures SAADC.RESOLUTION from arg1[0]
00023df4  // 3. Configures SAADC.OVERSAMPLE from arg1[1]
00023df4  // 4. Stores arg1[3] to data_200035da (low power mode flag)
00023df4  // 5. Sets initialized flag data_200035d8=1
00023df4  // 6. Initializes state variables: data_200035bc=0, data_200035d9=0,
00023df4  // etc.
00023df4  // 7. Clears all interrupts (INTENCLR=0x7fffffff)
00023df4  // 8. Clears EVENTS_END and EVENTS_STARTED
00023df4  // 9. Enables NVIC IRQ 7 with priority from arg1[2]
00023df4  // 10. Enables END interrupt (INTENSET=0x2)
00023df4  // 11. If low power mode: enables STARTED interrupt (INTENSET=0x1)
00023df4  // 12. Enables SAADC peripheral (ENABLE=1)
00023df4  // 
00023df4  // Returns 0 on success
00023df4  // SDK: components/drivers_nrf/saadc/nrf_drv_saadc.c
00023df4  254b       ldr     r3, [pc, #0x94]
00023df6  93f82c30   ldrb    r3, [r3, #0x2c]
00023dfa  002b       cmp     r3, #0
00023dfc  41d1       bne     #0x23e82

00023dfe  0029       cmp     r1, #0
00023e00  41d0       beq     #0x23e86

00023ef8    int32_t saadc_buffer_convert(struct arg1, struct arg2)

00023ef8  // Set SAADC result buffer. Provides buffer for ADC samples, triggers
00023ef8  // conversion when buffer is ready. Supports double-buffering for
00023ef8  // continuous sampling.
00023ef8  314b       ldr     r3, [pc, #0xc4]  {data_23fc0}  {SAADC}
00023efa  1222       movs    r2, #0x12
00023efc  c3f80823   str     r2, [r3, #0x308]  {0x12}  {SAADC.INTENCLR}

0002416c  void* data_2416c = data_200035ac

00024170    ret_code_t ppi_channel_assign(uint8_t channel, uint32_t eep, uint32_t tep)

00024170  // Assign event and task to PPI channel
00024170  // SDK: components/drivers_nrf/hal/nrf_ppi.h
00024170  // 
00024170  // Configures PPI (Programmable Peripheral Interconnect) channel.
00024170  // 
00024170  // PPI system:
00024170  // - Connects peripheral events to tasks without CPU intervention
00024170  // - 20 programmable channels (0-19)
00024170  // - 12 pre-programmed channels (20-31, fixed connections)
00024170  // - Zero latency eventtask propagation
00024170  // 
00024170  // PPI registers (base 0x4001f000):
00024170  // - CH[n].EEP: Event Endpoint (source event address)
00024170  // - CH[n].TEP: Task Endpoint (destination task address)
00024170  // - CHENSET: Channel Enable Set (write 1 to enable channel)
00024170  // - CHENCLR: Channel Enable Clear (write 1 to disable channel)
00024170  // - CHG[n]: Channel Group (group channels for group operations)
00024170  // 
00024170  // Common PPI use cases:
00024170  // 1. RTC COMPARE  ADC START:
00024170  //    - Periodic ADC sampling at fixed intervals
00024170  //    - EEP = &RTC2->EVENTS_COMPARE[0]
00024170  //    - TEP = &SAADC->TASKS_SAMPLE
00024170  // 2. GPIOTE IN  TIMER CAPTURE:
00024170  //    - Timestamp GPIO events with hardware precision
00024170  //    - EEP = &GPIOTE->EVENTS_IN[0]
00024170  //    - TEP = &TIMER0->TASKS_CAPTURE[0]
00024170  // 3. TIMER COMPARE  SPI START:
00024170  //    - Precise timed SPI transfers
00024170  //    - EEP = &TIMER1->EVENTS_COMPARE[0]
00024170  //    - TEP = &SPI0->TASKS_START
00024170  // 
00024170  // Parameters:
00024170  // - channel: PPI channel number (0-19)
00024170  // - event_addr: Address of peripheral event register
00024170  // - task_addr: Address of peripheral task register
00024170  // 
00024170  // Example:
00024170  // ```c
00024170  // ppi_channel_assign(0, 
00024170  //     (uint32_t)&RTC2->EVENTS_COMPARE[0],
00024170  //     (uint32_t)&SAADC->TASKS_SAMPLE);
00024170  // ppi_channel_enable(0);
00024170  // ```
00024170  // 
00024170  // Returns: void
00024170  12b3       cbz     r2, #0x241b8

00024172  38b5       push    {r3, r4, r5, lr} {var_4} {__saved_r5} {__saved_r4} {__saved_r3}
00024174  0446       mov     r4, r0
00024176  0d46       mov     r5, r1
00024178  1146       mov     r1, r2
0002417a  4379       ldrb    r3, [r0, #5]
0002417c  104a       ldr     r2, [pc, #0x40]  {data_241c0}  {data_200035e0}
0002417e  42f82310   str     r1, [r2, r3, lsl #2]
00024182  03eb4303   add     r3, r3, r3, lsl #1
00024186  0f4a       ldr     r2, [pc, #0x3c]  {data_241c4}  {data_200035dc}
00024188  d35c       ldrb    r3, [r2, r3]
0002418a  bbb9       cbnz    r3, #0x241bc

0002418c  a978       ldrb    r1, [r5, #2]
0002418e  90f90400   ldrsb   r0, [r0, #4]
00024192  fff7d7fb   bl      #nvic_set_priority_and_enable
00024196  2368       ldr     r3, [r4]
00024198  2a88       ldrh    r2, [r5]
0002419a  c3f80825   str     r2, [r3, #0x508]
0002419e  6379       ldrb    r3, [r4, #5]
000241a0  2879       ldrb    r0, [r5, #4]
000241a2  084a       ldr     r2, [pc, #0x20]  {data_241c4}  {data_200035dc}
000241a4  03eb4303   add     r3, r3, r3, lsl #1
000241a8  d118       adds    r1, r2, r3
000241aa  4870       strb    r0, [r1, #1]
000241ac  e878       ldrb    r0, [r5, #3]
000241ae  8870       strb    r0, [r1, #2]
000241b0  0121       movs    r1, #1
000241b2  d154       strb    r1, [r2, r3]  {0x1}
000241b4  0020       movs    r0, #0

000241b6  38bd       pop     {r3, r4, r5, pc} {__saved_r3} {__saved_r4} {__saved_r5} {var_4}

000241b8  0720       movs    r0, #7
000241ba  7047       bx      lr

000241bc  0820       movs    r0, #8
000241be  fae7       b       #0x241b6

000241c0  void* data_241c0 = data_200035e0
000241c4  int32_t data_241c4 = 0x200035dc

000241c8    void ppi_channel_enable(int32_t* arg1)

000241c8  // Enable PPI channel
000241c8  // SDK: components/drivers_nrf/hal/nrf_ppi.h
000241c8  // 
000241c8  // Enables a configured PPI channel for eventtask routing.
000241c8  // 
000241c8  // Enable mechanism:
000241c8  // - Write (1 << channel) to PPI->CHENSET register
000241c8  // - Channel begins routing events to tasks immediately
000241c8  // - No CPU intervention required once enabled
000241c8  // 
000241c8  // PPI channel states:
000241c8  // - Disabled (reset default): Events ignored, tasks not triggered
000241c8  // - Enabled: Events automatically trigger configured tasks
000241c8  // 
000241c8  // Channel enable pattern:
000241c8  // ```c
000241c8  // // Configure channel first
000241c8  // ppi_channel_assign(channel, event_addr, task_addr);
000241c8  // 
000241c8  // // Then enable
000241c8  // ppi_channel_enable(channel);  // Write PPI->CHENSET
000241c8  // 
000241c8  // // Channel now active, event automatically triggers task
000241c8  // ```
000241c8  // 
000241c8  // Channel disable:
000241c8  // - Write (1 << channel) to PPI->CHENCLR register
000241c8  // - Or call ppi_channel_disable(channel)
000241c8  // 
000241c8  // PPI latency:
000241c8  // - Event to task: ~1 cycle (16 MHz system clock = 62.5 ns)
000241c8  // - Much faster than interrupt (50-100+ cycles)
000241c8  // - Deterministic timing (no jitter)
000241c8  // 
000241c8  // Common usage pattern:
000241c8  // ```c
000241c8  // // Set up RTC2 to trigger ADC every 125ms
000241c8  // ppi_channel_assign(0, 
000241c8  //     (uint32_t)&RTC2->EVENTS_COMPARE[0],
000241c8  //     (uint32_t)&SAADC->TASKS_SAMPLE);
000241c8  // ppi_channel_enable(0);
000241c8  // // Now ADC samples automatically every RTC2 tick
000241c8  // ```
000241c8  // 
000241c8  // Parameters:
000241c8  // - channel: PPI channel number (0-19)
000241c8  // 
000241c8  // Returns: void
000241c8  0368       ldr     r3, [r0]
000241ca  0122       movs    r2, #1
000241cc  1a60       str     r2, [r3]
000241ce  4379       ldrb    r3, [r0, #5]
000241d0  03eb4303   add     r3, r3, r3, lsl #1
000241d4  014a       ldr     r2, [pc, #4]
000241d6  0221       movs    r1, #2
000241d8  d154       strb    r1, [r2, r3]
000241da  7047       bx      lr

000241dc  int32_t data_241dc = 0x200035dc

00024208    void RTC2_IRQHandler()

00024208  // RTC2 interrupt handler for periodic timekeeping
00024208  // SDK: Application-specific interrupt handler
00024208  // Handles RTC2 COMPARE[0] events for 125ms tick generation.
00024208  // Interrupt handling:
00024208  // 1. Check RTC2->EVENTS_COMPARE[0] (offset 0x140)
00024208  // 2. Clear event register: write 0 to EVENTS_COMPARE[0]
00024208  // 3. Update CC[0] register: Add 1 for next 125ms tick
00024208  // 4. Call rtc_125ms_tick_handler() for time processing
00024208  // 5. Return from interrupt
00024208  // RTC2 registers (base 0x40024000):
00024208  // - EVENTS_COMPARE[0] (0x140): Compare event flag
00024208  // - CC[0] (0x540): Compare register (next match value)
00024208  // - COUNTER (0x504): Current counter value
00024208  // Tick processing in rtc_125ms_tick_handler:
00024208  // - Increment tick counter at data_20004604
00024208  // - Every 8 ticks (1000ms): increment Unix time at data_20004600
00024208  // - Update UI display if time shown on LCD
00024208  // - Trigger time-dependent state machine transitions
00024208  // Interrupt priority: 3 (APP_LOW)
00024208  // NVIC IRQ: 21
00024208  // Called automatically: Every 125ms while RTC2 running
00024208  70b5       push    {r4, r5, r6, lr} {var_4} {__saved_r6} {__saved_r5} {__saved_r4}
0002420a  84b0       sub     sp, #0x10
0002420c  4ff4a074   mov     r4, #0x140
00024210  4ff48035   mov     r5, #0x10000
00024214  0026       movs    r6, #0
00024216  03e0       b       #0x24220

00024218  6d00       lsls    r5, r5, #1

00024408    int32_t twi_master_transfer(void* arg1, int32_t* arg2, int32_t* arg3, int32_t arg4)

00024408  // Execute TWI (I2C) transfer operation
00024408  // arg1: TWI peripheral base address
00024408  // arg2: State structure pointer
00024408  // arg3: Transfer descriptor (address, length, flags)
00024408  // arg4: Transfer flags (bit 0: stop condition, bit 1: restart, bit 2:
00024408  // no ACK, bit 3: direction)
00024408  // Returns 0 on success, 0x10 if invalid params, 0x11 if busy
00024408  // Supports both blocking and interrupt-driven transfers
00024408  // Sets EVENTS_STOPPED before starting transfer

000245a8  // Configures GPIO pins (SCL, SDA), frequency, interrupt priority
000245a8  // Stores config in state array at 0x20003600 (per-instance state)
000245a8  // Sets pin configurations: SCL output high, SDA open-drain pullup
000245a8  // Frequency modes: 0=100kHz, 1=250kHz, 2=400kHz

00024838  int32_t data_24838 = 0x200035e4
0002483c  int32_t data_2483c = -0x1fff1f00

00024840    int32_t twi_master_tx(void** arg1, int32_t* arg2, int32_t arg3)

00024840  // Transmit data via TWI (I2C) master
00024840  // Checks if transfer is in progress (state byte at 0x20003601)
00024840  // Pulls CS low before transfer (if pin configured)
00024840  // Copies transfer descriptor to state structure (16 bytes at
00024840  // 0x200035f0)
00024840  // Clears status flags in state byte (bits 0-2)
00024840  // If interrupt mode: calls twi_master_transfer()
00024840  // If blocking mode: calls twi_master_write()
00024840  // Returns 0x11 if busy, 6 if arg3==0, else transfer result

00024988    int32_t COMP_LPCOMP_IRQHandler()

00024988  // COMP/LPCOMP interrupt handler - processes comparator events
00024988  // Checks 4 event registers and calls comp_event_handler_call():
00024988  // - Offset 0x100: Event type 1 (UP crossing)
00024988  // - Offset 0x104: Event type 2 (DOWN crossing)
00024988  // - Offset 0x108: Event type 4 (CROSS event)
00024988  // - Offset 0x10c: Event type 8 (READY event)
00024988  // 
00024988  // Each call passes register offset and event type bitmask
00024988  // Callback dispatches to coin_cell_state_handler
00024988  // Used for battery voltage threshold detection
00024988  // Triggers when comparator detects voltage crossing reference
00024988  // SDK: components/drivers_nrf/comp/nrf_drv_comp.c
00024988  08b5       push    {r3, lr}
0002498a  0121       movs    r1, #1
0002498c  4ff48070   mov     r0, #0x100
00024990  fff7dcff   bl      #0x2494c
00024994  0221       movs    r1, #2
00024996  4ff48270   mov     r0, #0x104
0002499a  fff7d7ff   bl      #0x2494c
0002499e  0421       movs    r1, #4
000249a0  4ff48470   mov     r0, #0x108
000249a4  fff7d2ff   bl      #0x2494c
000249a8  0821       movs    r1, #8
000249aa  4ff48670   mov     r0, #0x10c
000249ae  fff7cdff   bl      #0x2494c
000249b2  08bd       pop     {r3, pc}


000249b4    int32_t comp_init(int32_t* arg1, int32_t arg2)

000249b4  // Initialize COMP (Comparator) peripheral
000249b4  // arg1: Config structure pointer
000249b4  // arg2: Event handler callback
000249b4  // Returns 8 if already initialized (data_20003630==1)
000249b4  // Returns 7 if no callback provided (arg2==0)
000249b4  // 
000249b4  // Configuration sequence:
000249b4  // 1. Stops COMP via TASKS_STOP, disables via ENABLE=0
000249b4  // 2. Sets REFSEL register from arg1[0] bits 0-3 (reference voltage)
000249b4  //    - If bits 0-2 == 7: Sets EXTREFSEL from arg1[0] bit 16
000249b4  // 3. Sets ANADETECT from arg1[1] bits 0-1 (analog detection mode)
000249b4  // 4. Sets HYST from arg1[5] bit 0 (hysteresis enable)
000249b4  // 5. Clears SHORTS and all interrupts (INTENCLR=0xf)
000249b4  // 6. Stores callback at data_2000362c
000249b4  // 7. Configures PSEL pin from arg1[2] (preserves bits 3-31)
000249b4  // 8. Enables interrupts based on arg1[1]:
000249b4  //    - Mode 1: INTENSET=0x4 (UP event)
000249b4  //    - Mode 2: INTENSET=0x2 (DOWN event)
000249b4  //    - Mode 0: INTENSET=0x8 (CROSS event)
000249b4  //    - Sets SHORTS.READY_SAMPLE=1 (auto-sample on ready)
000249b4  // 9. Enables NVIC IRQ 19 with priority from arg1[9]
000249b4  // 10. Sets initialized flag data_20003630=1
000249b4  // 
000249b4  // Returns 0 on success
000249b4  // SDK: components/drivers_nrf/comp/nrf_drv_comp.c
000249b4  344b       ldr     r3, [pc, #0xd0]
000249b6  1b78       ldrb    r3, [r3]
000249b8  002b       cmp     r3, #0
000249ba  60d1       bne     #0x24a7e

000249bc  334b       ldr     r3, [pc, #0xcc]
000249be  0122       movs    r2, #1

000249da  3bd0       beq     #0x24a54

00024b4c    int32_t spi_start_transfer(int32_t* arg1, int32_t* arg2, int32_t arg3, int32_t arg4)

00024b4c  // SDK: components/drivers_nrf/spi_master/nrf_drv_spi.c - start SPI
00024b4c  // transfer operation
00024b4c  10b4       push    {r4} {__saved_r4}
00024b4e  83b0       sub     sp, #0xc
00024b50  0224       movs    r4, #2

00024b62  12f0080f   tst     r2, #8

00024c44    uint32_t spi_init(void* p_instance, void* p_config, void* event_handler)

00024c44  // Initialize SPI0 peripheral
00024c44  // SDK: components/drivers_nrf/spi_master/nrf_drv_spi.c
00024c44  // Configures SPI0 for external flash and LCD communication.
00024c44  // SPI0 configuration (base 0x40003000):
00024c44  // - PSEL.SCK: Pin select for clock (SCK)
00024c44  // - PSEL.MOSI: Pin select for Master Out Slave In
00024c44  // - PSEL.MISO: Pin select for Master In Slave Out
00024c44  // - FREQUENCY: SPI clock frequency
00024c44  // - CONFIG: Mode, bit order, phase/polarity
00024c44  // SPI frequency options:
00024c44  // - 125 kHz: 0x02000000
00024c44  // - 250 kHz: 0x04000000
00024c44  // - 500 kHz: 0x08000000
00024c44  // - 1 MHz: 0x10000000
00024c44  // - 2 MHz: 0x20000000
00024c44  // - 4 MHz: 0x40000000 (typical for external flash)
00024c44  // - 8 MHz: 0x80000000 (maximum, may have signal integrity issues)
00024c44  // SPI mode configuration (CONFIG register):
00024c44  // - CPOL (Clock Polarity): 0 = idle low, 1 = idle high
00024c44  // - CPHA (Clock Phase): 0 = sample on leading edge, 1 = trailing edge
00024c44  // - ORDER: MSBFIRST (0) or LSBFIRST (1)
00024c44  // - Mode 0: CPOL=0, CPHA=0 (most common for flash)
00024c44  // Pin configuration:
00024c44  // - External flash CS: Separate GPIO (toggled manually)
00024c44  // - LCD CS: Separate GPIO (toggled manually)
00024c44  // - Shared MOSI, MISO, SCK between flash and LCD
00024c44  // DMA support (Easy DMA):
00024c44  // - RXD.PTR: Pointer to receive buffer
00024c44  // - RXD.MAXCNT: Max receive bytes
00024c44  // - TXD.PTR: Pointer to transmit buffer
00024c44  // - TXD.MAXCNT: Max transmit bytes
00024c44  // Interrupt configuration:
00024c44  // - NVIC IRQ 3 (SPI0_TWI0_IRQHandler)
00024c44  // - Priority: Typically 0xe0 (APP_LOW)
00024c44  // - Events: END (transfer complete)
00024c44  // Called from: ext_flash_spi_init(), lcd_spi_init()
00024c44  // Returns: 0 on success
00024c44  f0b5       push    {r4, r5, r6, r7, lr} {var_4} {__saved_r7} {__saved_r6} {__saved_r5} {__saved_r4}
00024c46  85b0       sub     sp, #0x14

00024d48    int32_t spi_transfer(int32_t* arg1, int32_t* arg2, int32_t arg3, int32_t arg4)

00024d48  // Perform SPI transfer (blocking or async)
00024d48  // SDK: components/drivers_nrf/spi_master/nrf_drv_spi.c
00024d48  // Executes SPI transfer with transmit and/or receive buffers.
00024d48  // Parameters:
00024d48  // - p_tx_buffer: Pointer to transmit data (NULL if receive-only)
00024d48  // - tx_buffer_length: Number of bytes to transmit
00024d48  // - p_rx_buffer: Pointer to receive buffer (NULL if transmit-only)
00024d48  // - rx_buffer_length: Number of bytes to receive
00024d48  // Transfer modes:
00024d48  // 1. Transmit-only: p_tx_buffer != NULL, p_rx_buffer == NULL
00024d48  // 2. Receive-only: p_tx_buffer == NULL, p_rx_buffer != NULL (sends
00024d48  // 0x00)
00024d48  // 3. Full-duplex: Both buffers != NULL (simultaneous TX/RX)
00024d48  // 
00024d48  // Transfer implementation:
00024d48  // 1. Set up DMA pointers:
00024d48  //    - TXD.PTR = p_tx_buffer (or dummy buffer if NULL)
00024d48  //    - RXD.PTR = p_rx_buffer (or dummy buffer if NULL)
00024d48  //    - TXD.MAXCNT = tx_buffer_length
00024d48  //    - RXD.MAXCNT = rx_buffer_length
00024d48  // 2. Trigger transfer: TASKS_START = 1
00024d48  // 3. Wait for completion:
00024d48  //    - Blocking mode: Poll EVENTS_END
00024d48  //    - Async mode: Return immediately, callback on END interrupt
00024d48  // 
00024d48  // SPI usage patterns:
00024d48  // - External flash commands:
00024d48  //   * Write Enable: TX [0x06]
00024d48  //   * Read Status: TX [0x05], RX [status]
00024d48  //   * Read Data: TX [0x03, addr_hi, addr_mid, addr_lo], RX [data...]
00024d48  // - LCD commands:
00024d48  //   * Write command: TX [cmd]
00024d48  //   * Write data: TX [data...]
00024d48  // 
00024d48  // Transfer constraints:
00024d48  // - Max length: 255 bytes per transfer (MAXCNT 8-bit)
00024d48  // - For longer transfers: Split into multiple calls
00024d48  // - CS must be manually controlled (not automatic)
00024d48  // 
00024d48  // Returns: 0 on success, NRF_ERROR_BUSY if transfer already active
00024d48  38b5       push    {r3, r4, r5, lr} {var_10} {var_4} {__saved_r5} {__saved_r4}
00024d4a  8c46       mov     r12, r1
00024d4c  0479       ldrb    r4, [r0, #4]
00024d4e  2149       ldr     r1, [pc, #0x84]  {data_24dd4}  {data_20003634}

00024dec    void reset_entry_point() __noreturn

00024dec  // Trigger system reset via NVIC
00024dec  // Initializes stack variables to 0 (var_14, var_10, var_c)
00024dec  // Calls NVIC_SystemReset() to perform ARM Cortex-M4 system reset

00024e0c    void NVIC_SystemReset() __noreturn

00024e0c  // NVIC System Reset. Checks if debugger attached (DHCSR 0xe000edf0),
00024e0c  // DSB barriers, writes AIRCR register (0xe000ed0c) with VECTKEY 0x5fa
00024e0c  // and SYSRESETREQ bit. From CMSIS core_cm4.h

000254ac    int32_t app_timer_stop_rtc()

000254ac  // Stops RTC1 timer. Disables IRQ 17 (0xe000e180), DSB/ISB barriers,
000254ac  // disables RTC1 event and interrupt for COMPARE[0], stops RTC1,
000254ac  // clears counter and data_20003758, sets data_20003749=0. From SDK
000254ac  // app_timer.c
000254ac  30b4       push    {r4, r5} {__saved_r5} {__saved_r4}
000254ae  4e4b       ldr     r3, [pc, #0x138]  {data_255e8}  {0xe000e100}
000254b0  4ff40032   mov     r2, #0x20000
000254b4  c3f88020   str     r2, [r3, #0x80]  {0x20000}  {0xe000e180}
000254b8  bff34f8f   dsb     SY
000254bc  bff36f8f   isb     SY
000254c0  02f18042   add     r2, r2, #0x40000000
000254c4  a2f57042   sub     r2, r2, #0xf000  {RTC1}
000254c8  4ff48033   mov     r3, #0x10000

000255fc    void app_timer_update_compare()

000255fc  // Update RTC1 compare register (CC0) for next app_timer expiration.
000255fc  // Reads timer list head (g_app_timer_list_head) for next timeout
000255fc  // value.
000255fc  // Calculates RTC1.CC0 value accounting for 24-bit rollover and 3-tick
000255fc  // margin.
000255fc  // Starts RTC if stopped. Enables IRQ17 (RTC1) interrupt.
000255fc  // If next expiration already passed, immediately triggers by setting
000255fc  // CC0=COUNTER.
000255fc  // From SDK components/libraries/timer/app_timer module.

0002577c    ret_code_t app_timer_init()

0002577c  // Initialize app_timer module
0002577c  // SDK: components/libraries/timer/app_timer.c
0002577c  // 
0002577c  // Initializes the app_timer system for software timers.
0002577c  // 
0002577c  // Initialization process:
0002577c  // 1. Configure RTC1 peripheral for timer base
0002577c  // 2. Set PRESCALER register (APP_TIMER_PRESCALER from sdk_config.h)
0002577c  // 3. Initialize timer list data structures at data_20003f00
0002577c  // 4. Enable RTC1 interrupt (NVIC IRQ 17)
0002577c  // 5. Start RTC1 counter (TASKS_START)
0002577c  // 
0002577c  // RTC1 configuration (base 0x4000b000):
0002577c  // - PRESCALER: Divide 32.768 kHz by (PRESCALER+1)
0002577c  //   * Value 0: 32768 Hz (30.5 us per tick)
0002577c  //   * Value 15: 2048 Hz (488 us per tick, typical)
0002577c  //   * Value 4095: 8 Hz (122 ms per tick)
0002577c  // - CC[0-3]: Compare channels for timer events
0002577c  // - INTENSET: Enable COMPARE[0] interrupt
0002577c  // - EVTEN: Enable events for PPI
0002577c  // 
0002577c  // Timer infrastructure:
0002577c  // - Max timers: Typically 10-20 (APP_TIMER_MAX_TIMERS)
0002577c  // - Timer modes: Single-shot, repeated
0002577c  // - Timer resolution: Determined by PRESCALER
0002577c  // - Minimum timeout: 5 ticks (APP_TIMER_MIN_TIMEOUT_TICKS)
0002577c  // 
0002577c  // Timer list storage: data_20003f00
0002577c  // - Active timer linked list
0002577c  // - Sorted by expiration time
0002577c  // - Updated in SWI0 interrupt handler
0002577c  // 
0002577c  // Called from: init_routine() early in system initialization
0002577c  // Returns: 0 (NRF_SUCCESS) on success
0002577c  10b5       push    {r4, lr}
0002577e  fff795fe   bl      #0x254ac
00025782  0f4b       ldr     r3, [pc, #0x3c]
00025784  0024       movs    r4, #0
00025786  // Initialize g_cmd_queue_head = 0 (app_timer command queue head
00025786  // index)
00025786  1c70       strb    r4, [r3]
00025788  // Initialize g_cmd_queue_tail = 0 (app_timer command queue tail
00025788  // index)
00025788  5c70       strb    r4, [r3, #1]
0002578a  0b22       movs    r2, #0xb
0002578c  // Initialize g_cmd_queue_size = 11 (max entries in command queue)
0002578c  9a70       strb    r2, [r3, #2]
0002578e  0d4b       ldr     r3, [pc, #0x34]
00025790  // Initialize g_app_timer_list_head = NULL (linked list of active
00025790  // timers)
00025790  1c60       str     r4, [r3]
00025792  0d4b       ldr     r3, [pc, #0x34]
00025794  // Initialize g_app_timer_circ_head = 0 (circular buffer head for RTC
00025794  // timestamps)
00025794  1c70       strb    r4, [r3]
00025796  0d4b       ldr     r3, [pc, #0x34]
00025798  // Initialize g_app_timer_circ_tail = 0 (circular buffer tail for RTC
00025798  // timestamps)
00025798  1c70       strb    r4, [r3]
0002579a  0d4b       ldr     r3, [pc, #0x34]
0002579c  4ff48012   mov     r2, #0x100000
000257a0  c3f88021   str     r2, [r3, #0x180]
000257a4  e021       movs    r1, #0xe0
000257a6  83f81413   strb    r1, [r3, #0x314]
000257aa  1a60       str     r2, [r3]
000257ac  2046       mov     r0, r4
000257ae  fff7c1fb   bl      #0x24f34
000257b2  084b       ldr     r3, [pc, #0x20]
000257b4  d3f80425   ldr     r2, [r3, #0x504]
000257b8  074b       ldr     r3, [pc, #0x1c]
000257ba  // Initialize g_rtc_timestamp from RTC1.COUNTER (24-bit counter at
000257ba  // 32.768 kHz)
000257ba  1a60       str     r2, [r3]
000257bc  2046       mov     r0, r4
000257be  10bd       pop     {r4, pc}

000257c0  int32_t data_257c0 = 0x2000363c
000257c4  int32_t data_257c4 = 0x2000375c
000257c8  int32_t data_257c8 = 0x20003754
000257cc  int32_t data_257cc = 0x20003755
000257d0  int32_t data_257d0 = -0x1fff1f00

00025808    int32_t app_timer_start(void* arg1, int32_t arg2, int32_t arg3)

00025808  // Start app_timer with specified timeout. Enqueues start command to
00025808  // SWI0, command processor inserts timer into active list. From SDK
00025808  // components/libraries/timer/app_timer.c.
00025808  08b5       push    {r3, lr}
0002580a  1346       mov     r3, r2

00025bbc    int32_t sd_ble_enable()

00025bbc  // Enable BLE stack in SoftDevice
00025bbc  // SDK: components/softdevice/s132/headers/ble.h
00025bbc  // 
00025bbc  // Initializes and enables the BLE protocol stack in SoftDevice.
00025bbc  // 
00025bbc  // SVC call: Supervisor Call to SoftDevice (SVC number 0x60)
00025bbc  // Parameters passed to SoftDevice:
00025bbc  // - app_ram_base: Base address for application RAM (must be after
00025bbc  // SoftDevice)
00025bbc  // - ble_enable_params_t: BLE configuration structure
00025bbc  // 
00025bbc  // BLE enable parameters:
00025bbc  // - vs_uuid_count: Number of vendor-specific UUIDs (128-bit)
00025bbc  // - gatts_enable_params: GATT Server config (attr table size, service
00025bbc  // changed)
00025bbc  // - gap_enable_params: GAP config (periph/central, max connections)
00025bbc  // - common_enable_params: Common config (vendor-specific features)
00025bbc  // 
00025bbc  // RAM requirement calculation:
00025bbc  // - SoftDevice base: 0x20000000
00025bbc  // - SoftDevice RAM: ~12-20KB (depends on config)
00025bbc  // - app_ram_base: Typically 0x20003000 for S132 v5.1.0
00025bbc  // - Application RAM: Remaining space to 0x20010000 (64KB total)
00025bbc  // 
00025bbc  // Initialization sequence (must be called before):
00025bbc  // 1. sd_softdevice_enable() - Enable SoftDevice
00025bbc  // 2. sd_nvic_EnableIRQ(SD_EVT_IRQn) - Enable SoftDevice events
00025bbc  // 3. sd_ble_enable() - Enable BLE stack (this function)
00025bbc  // 4. Configure GAP/GATT services

00025bbc  // Returns: 0 (NRF_SUCCESS) on success, error code on failure

00025bc0  164b       ldr     r3, [pc, #0x58]
00025bc2  1b78       ldrb    r3, [r3]
00025bc4  1bbb       cbnz    r3, #0x25c0e

00025ffc    uint32_t ble_operation_check_result()

00025ffc  // Check BLE operation result from SoftDevice SVC call.
00025ffc  // Calls sd_svc_wrapper_8() and validates return code.
00025ffc  // Returns 1 if r0==0 (success), 0 otherwise.
00025ffc  // Ignores 0x11 (NRF_ERROR_BUSY), invokes callback for other errors.
00025ffc  // Uses __clz (count leading zeros) for boolean conversion.
00025ffc  10b5       push    {r4, lr}
00025ffe  fff7a7ff   bl      #0x25f50
00026002  0446       mov     r4, r0
00026004  08b1       cbz     r0, #0x2600a

00026010  10bd       pop     {r4, pc}

000261d8    void ble_conn_params_on_ble_evt(int16_t* arg1)

000261d8  // Handle connection parameter negotiation events
000261d8  // SDK: components/ble/ble_services/ble_conn_params/ble_conn_params.c
000261d8  // 
000261d8  // Manages BLE connection parameter updates and negotiation.
000261d8  // Handles BLE_GAP_EVT_CONNECTED (0x10) and
000261d8  // BLE_GAP_EVT_CONN_PARAM_UPDATE_REQUEST (0x12).
000261d8  // 
000261d8  // Connection parameters negotiated:
000261d8  // - Min connection interval: 7.5ms - 4000ms (units of 1.25ms)
000261d8  // - Max connection interval: 7.5ms - 4000ms (units of 1.25ms)
000261d8  // - Slave latency: 0-499 intervals
000261d8  // - Supervision timeout: 100ms - 32000ms (units of 10ms)
000261d8  // 
000261d8  // On CONNECTED: Starts negotiation timer
000261d8  // On UPDATE_REQUEST: Validates and accepts/rejects parameters
000261d8  // 
000261d8  // Parameters:
000261d8  // - arg1: ble_evt_t* event structure
000261d8  // 
000261d8  // Returns: Updates connection handle at data_20003abc
000261d8  08b5       push    {r3, lr}
000261da  0388       ldrh    r3, [r0]
000261dc  122b       cmp     r3, #0x12
000261de  0fd0       beq     #0x26200

000261e0  06d8       bhi     #0x261f0

000261e2  102b       cmp     r3, #0x10
000261e4  09d0       beq     #0x261fa

000261e6  112b       cmp     r3, #0x11
000261e8  09d1       bne     #0x261fe

000261ea  fff74bff   bl      #0x26084
000261ee  06e0       b       #0x261fe

000261f0  502b       cmp     r3, #0x50
000261f2  04d1       bne     #0x261fe

000261f4  fff7c8ff   bl      #0x26188
000261f8  01e0       b       #0x261fe

000261fa  fff77bff   bl      #0x260f4

000261fe  08bd       pop     {r3, pc}

00026200  fff7aaff   bl      #0x26158
00026204  fbe7       b       #0x261fe

00026206                    00 00                                                                                ..

00026298    int32_t sd_ble_gap_adv_start()

00026298  // Start BLE advertising
00026298  // SDK: components/softdevice/s132/headers/ble_gap.h
00026298  // 
00026298  // Starts BLE advertising with configured parameters.
00026298  // 
00026298  // SVC call: Supervisor Call to SoftDevice (SVC number 0x6C)
00026298  // Parameters:
00026298  // - adv_handle: Advertising set handle (0 for legacy advertising)
00026298  // - conn_cfg_tag: Connection configuration tag (link to conn params)
00026298  // 
00026298  // Advertising must be configured first with:
00026298  // - sd_ble_gap_adv_set_configure(): Set advertising data, scan
00026298  // response, params
00026298  // 
00026298  // Advertising parameters (ble_gap_adv_params_t):
00026298  // - interval: 20ms to 10.24s (units of 0.625ms)
00026298  //   * Fast: 20-30ms (32-48 units)
00026298  //   * Slow: 1000-1285ms (1600-2056 units)
00026298  // - timeout: 0-180s (0 = infinite)
00026298  // - channel_mask: Channels 37, 38, 39 (typically all 3)
00026298  // - filter_policy: Allow all or whitelist only
00026298  // 
00026298  // Advertising data format:
00026298  // - Max 31 bytes for advertising data
00026298  // - Max 31 bytes for scan response data
00026298  // - AD structures: [length, type, data...]
00026298  // 
00026298  // Common AD types:
00026298  // - 0x01: Flags (LE General/Limited Discoverable, BR/EDR support)
00026298  // - 0x02/0x03: 16-bit UUIDs (incomplete/complete list)
00026298  // - 0x06/0x07: 128-bit UUIDs (incomplete/complete list)
00026298  // - 0x09: Complete local name
00026298  // 
00026298  // Returns: 0 on success, NRF_ERROR_INVALID_STATE if already
00026298  // advertising
00026298  6ddf       svc     #0x6d
0002629a  7047       bx      lr


0002629c    int32_t sd_ble_gap_adv_stop()

0002629c  // Stop BLE advertising
0002629c  // SDK: components/softdevice/s132/headers/ble_gap.h
0002629c  // 
0002629c  // Stops ongoing BLE advertising.
0002629c  // 
0002629c  // SVC call: Supervisor Call to SoftDevice (SVC number 0x6D)
0002629c  // Parameters:
0002629c  // - adv_handle: Advertising set handle (0 for legacy advertising)
0002629c  // 
0002629c  // Stop triggers:
0002629c  // - Explicit call to sd_ble_gap_adv_stop()
0002629c  // - BLE_GAP_EVT_CONNECTED received (auto-stop on connection)
0002629c  // - Advertising timeout reached (if configured in adv_params)
0002629c  // - BLE_GAP_EVT_ADV_SET_TERMINATED event
0002629c  // 
0002629c  // Events generated:
0002629c  // - None if explicitly stopped
0002629c  // - BLE_GAP_EVT_TIMEOUT if timeout-based stop
0002629c  // - BLE_GAP_EVT_CONNECTED if connection-based stop
0002629c  // 
0002629c  // Use cases:
0002629c  // - Transition from fast to slow advertising
0002629c  // - Stop advertising during firmware update
0002629c  // - Battery saving mode (stop advertising, enter sleep)
0002629c  // - User-initiated "invisible mode"
0002629c  // 
0002629c  // After stopping:
0002629c  // - Can restart with sd_ble_gap_adv_start()
0002629c  // - Can reconfigure with sd_ble_gap_adv_set_configure()
0002629c  // - Radio automatically disabled to save power
0002629c  // 
0002629c  // Returns: 0 on success, NRF_ERROR_INVALID_STATE if not advertising
0002629c  72df       svc     #0x72
0002629e  7047       bx      lr

00026926    int32_t sd_ble_gap_conn_param_update()

00026926  // Update BLE connection parameters
00026926  // SDK: components/softdevice/s132/headers/ble_gap.h
00026926  // 
00026926  // Requests update of connection parameters for active connection.
00026926  // 
00026926  // SVC call: Supervisor Call to SoftDevice (SVC number 0x77)
00026926  // Parameters:
00026926  // - conn_handle: Connection handle to update
00026926  // - conn_params: Pointer to new connection parameters
00026926  // 
00026926  // Connection parameters (ble_gap_conn_params_t):
00026926  // - min_conn_interval: 7.5ms to 4000ms (units of 1.25ms)
00026926  // - max_conn_interval: 7.5ms to 4000ms (units of 1.25ms)
00026926  // - slave_latency: 0 to 499 (number of events peripheral can skip)
00026926  // - conn_sup_timeout: 100ms to 32000ms (units of 10ms, must be >
00026926  // interval)
00026926  // 
00026926  // Typical configurations:
00026926  // - High throughput: 7.5-15ms interval, 0 latency
00026926  // - Balanced: 30-50ms interval, 0-4 latency
00026926  // - Low power: 100-500ms interval, 4-30 latency
00026926  // 
00026926  // Parameter negotiation:
00026926  // 1. Peripheral sends LL_CONNECTION_PARAM_REQ
00026926  // 2. Central accepts/rejects via LL_CONNECTION_PARAM_RSP
00026926  // 3. On accept: BLE_GAP_EVT_CONN_PARAM_UPDATE event
00026926  // 4. On reject: BLE_GAP_EVT_CONN_PARAM_UPDATE_REQUEST with rejection
00026926  // 
00026926  // Constraint: conn_sup_timeout > (1 + slave_latency) *
00026926  // max_conn_interval * 2
00026926  // 
00026926  // Use cases:
00026926  // - Switch to high-speed for firmware transfer
00026926  // - Reduce power during idle periods
00026926  // - Optimize for UI responsiveness
00026926  // 
00026926  // Returns: 0 on success, NRF_ERROR_INVALID_PARAM if constraints
00026926  // violated
00026926  73df       svc     #0x73
00026928  7047       bx      lr

00026960    void ble_conn_handle_store(void* arg1, void* arg2)

00026960  // Store BLE connection handle
00026960  // SDK: Application-specific connection management
00026960  // 
00026960  // Stores connection handle for active BLE connection.
00026960  // 
00026960  // Connection handle:
00026960  // - Assigned by SoftDevice on BLE_GAP_EVT_CONNECTED
00026960  // - Valid range: 0x0000 to 0x00FF
00026960  // - Invalid handle: BLE_CONN_HANDLE_INVALID (0xFFFF)
00026960  // 
00026960  // Storage location: data_20003abc
00026960  // - Single connection supported (peripheral role only)
00026960  // - Overwritten if already connected (should not happen)
00026960  // 
00026960  // Connection handle uses:
00026960  // - sd_ble_gap_disconnect(conn_handle, reason)
00026960  // - sd_ble_gap_conn_param_update(conn_handle, params)
00026960  // - sd_ble_gatts_hvx(conn_handle, hvx_params)
00026960  // - sd_ble_gap_authenticate(conn_handle, sec_params)
00026960  // - pm_peer_id_get(conn_handle)
00026960  // 
00026960  // Connection lifecycle:
00026960  // 1. BLE_GAP_EVT_CONNECTED: Call ble_conn_handle_store(handle)
00026960  // 2. Active connection: Use stored handle for operations
00026960  // 3. BLE_GAP_EVT_DISCONNECTED: Clear handle to
00026960  // BLE_CONN_HANDLE_INVALID
00026960  // 
00026960  // Connection state at data_20003ac0:
00026960  // - conn_handle: Active connection handle
00026960  // - conn_state: Connected, disconnected, advertising
00026960  // - peer_id: Peer manager ID for bonded peer
00026960  // 
00026960  // Parameters:
00026960  // - arg1: uint16_t connection handle to store
00026960  // 
00026960  // Called from: BLE_GAP_EVT_CONNECTED handler in ble_evt_router
00026960  cb7b       ldrb    r3, [r1, #0xf]
00026962  012b       cmp     r3, #1
00026964  00d0       beq     #0x26968

00026966  7047       bx      lr

00026968  8b88       ldrh    r3, [r1, #4]
0002696a  a0f8c830   strh    r3, [r0, #0xc8]
0002696e  fae7       b       #0x26966

00026a7a    int32_t ble_advertising_init(char* arg1, char* arg2)

00026a7a  // Initialize BLE advertising module
00026a7a  // SDK: components/ble/ble_advertising/ble_advertising.c
00026a7a  // 
00026a7a  // Configures BLE advertising with parameters and data.
00026a7a  // 
00026a7a  // Parameters:
00026a7a  // - p_init: ble_advertising_init_t structure with configuration
00026a7a  // 
00026a7a  // Advertising configuration (ble_advertising_init_t):
00026a7a  // - advdata: Advertising data (name, flags, UUIDs, manufacturer data)
00026a7a  // - srdata: Scan response data (extended info, service UUIDs)
00026a7a  // - config: Advertising parameters (intervals, timeout, filter
00026a7a  // policy)
00026a7a  // 
00026a7a  // Advertising data (advdata):
00026a7a  // - name_type: BLE_ADVDATA_FULL_NAME or SHORT_NAME
00026a7a  // - include_appearance: Device appearance (keyboard, mouse, etc.)
00026a7a  // - flags: BLE_GAP_ADV_FLAGS_LE_ONLY_GENERAL_DISC_MODE
00026a7a  // - uuids_complete: Complete list of 16-bit/128-bit service UUIDs
00026a7a  // - manufacturer_data: Vendor-specific data (company ID + payload)
00026a7a  // 
00026a7a  // Advertising intervals (config.ble_adv_fast_interval,
00026a7a  // slow_interval):
00026a7a  // - Fast: 20-30ms (for quick discovery, 180s timeout)
00026a7a  // - Slow: 1000-1285ms (for battery saving, infinite timeout)
00026a7a  // 
00026a7a  // Configuration stored at: data_20003b00
00026a7a  // - Current advertising mode (fast/slow/idle)
00026a7a  // - Connection handle when connected
00026a7a  // - Event handler for advertising events
00026a7a  // 
00026a7a  // Initialization sequence:
00026a7a  // 1. Parse advdata and srdata into advertising packets
00026a7a  // 2. Configure advertising parameters for fast/slow modes
00026a7a  // 3. Call sd_ble_gap_adv_set_configure() for both modes
00026a7a  // 4. Register event handler with ble_advertising_on_ble_evt
00026a7a  // 5. Ready to start with ble_advertising_start()
00026a7a  // 
00026a7a  // Returns: 0 on success, NRF_ERROR_INVALID_PARAM if config invalid
00026a7a  0029       cmp     r1, #0
00026a7c  00f0a880   beq     #0x26bd0

00026a80  f8b5       push    {r3, r4, r5, r6, r7, lr} {var_4} {__saved_r7} {__saved_r6} {__saved_r5} {__saved_r4} {__saved_r3}

00026bd8    uint32_t ble_advertising_start(uint8_t advertising_mode)

00026bd8  // Start BLE advertising with configured mode
00026bd8  // SDK: components/ble/ble_advertising/ble_advertising.c
00026bd8  // 
00026bd8  // Starts BLE advertising using previously configured parameters.
00026bd8  // 
00026bd8  // Parameters:
00026bd8  // - erase_bonds: If true, delete all bonded peers before advertising
00026bd8  // 
00026bd8  // Advertising modes:
00026bd8  // - BLE_ADV_MODE_FAST: Fast advertising (20-30ms interval, 180s
00026bd8  // timeout)
00026bd8  // - BLE_ADV_MODE_SLOW: Slow advertising (1000-1285ms interval,
00026bd8  // infinite)
00026bd8  // - BLE_ADV_MODE_DIRECTED: Directed advertising to specific peer
00026bd8  // (1.28s timeout)
00026bd8  // - BLE_ADV_MODE_DIRECTED_SLOW: Low duty directed advertising
00026bd8  // 
00026bd8  // Erase bonds behavior:
00026bd8  // 1. If erase_bonds == true:
00026bd8  //    - Call pm_peers_delete() to remove all bonded peers
00026bd8  //    - Wait for PM_EVT_PEERS_DELETE_SUCCEEDED
00026bd8  //    - Clear whitelist
00026bd8  //    - Start advertising without filter
00026bd8  // 2. If erase_bonds == false:
00026bd8  //    - Start advertising with current settings
00026bd8  //    - May use whitelist if configured
00026bd8  // 
00026bd8  // Advertising start sequence:
00026bd8  // 1. Check current advertising state (must be idle)
00026bd8  // 2. Select advertising mode based on config
00026bd8  // 3. Call sd_ble_gap_adv_start() with adv_handle and conn_cfg_tag
00026bd8  // 4. Update advertising state at data_20003b00
00026bd8  // 5. Start timeout timer if configured
00026bd8  // 
00026bd8  // Typical call flow:
00026bd8  // 1. ble_advertising_init() - Configure advertising
00026bd8  // 2. ble_advertising_start(false) - Start advertising
00026bd8  // 3. On BLE_GAP_EVT_CONNECTED: Advertising auto-stops
00026bd8  // 4. On BLE_GAP_EVT_DISCONNECTED: Advertising auto-restarts
00026bd8  // 
00026bd8  // Returns: 0 on success, NRF_ERROR_INVALID_STATE if already
00026bd8  // advertising
00026bd8  0378       ldrb    r3, [r0]
00026bda  002b       cmp     r3, #0
00026bdc  00f08180   beq     #0x26ce2

00026be0  30b5       push    {r4, r5, lr} {var_4} {__saved_r5} {__saved_r4}
00026be2  85b0       sub     sp, #0x14
00026be4  0446       mov     r4, r0
00026be6  0d46       mov     r5, r1
00026be8  c170       strb    r1, [r0, #3]
00026bea  fff73eff   bl      #ble_advertising_init_handler
00026bee  20b1       cbz     r0, #0x26bfa

00026bf0  0123       movs    r3, #1
00026bf2  6370       strb    r3, [r4, #1]
00026bf4  0020       movs    r0, #0

00026bf6  05b0       add     sp, #0x14
00026bf8  30bd       pop     {r4, r5, pc} {__saved_r4} {__saved_r5} {var_4}

00026bfa  0722       movs    r2, #7
00026bfc  0021       movs    r1, #0
00026bfe  04f12500   add     r0, r4, #0x25
00026c02  fcf793fb   bl      #memset
00026c06  e388       ldrh    r3, [r4, #6]
00026c08  13b1       cbz     r3, #0x26c10

00026c0a  e378       ldrb    r3, [r4, #3]
00026c0c  012b       cmp     r3, #1
00026c0e  25d0       beq     #0x26c5c

00026c10  e379       ldrb    r3, [r4, #7]
00026c12  13b1       cbz     r3, #0x26c1a

00026c14  e378       ldrb    r3, [r4, #3]
00026c16  022b       cmp     r3, #2
00026c18  20d0       beq     #0x26c5c

00026c1a  2946       mov     r1, r5
00026c1c  2046       mov     r0, r4
00026c1e  fff7a7fe   bl      #ble_conn_params_get_next_mode
00026c22  e070       strb    r0, [r4, #3]
00026c24  d4f8cc30   ldr     r3, [r4, #0xcc]
00026c28  1bb1       cbz     r3, #0x26c32

00026c2a  0338       subs    r0, #3
00026c2c  c0b2       uxtb    r0, r0
00026c2e  0128       cmp     r0, #1
00026c30  21d9       bls     #0x26c76

00026c32  0023       movs    r3, #0

00026c38  1022       movs    r2, #0x10
00026c3a  0021       movs    r1, #0
00026c3c  6846       mov     r0, sp {var_20}

00026d40    uint32_t ble_advertising_on_ble_evt(int16_t* arg1, uint32_t arg2)

00026d40  // Handle advertising state machine events
00026d40  // SDK: components/ble/ble_advertising/ble_advertising.c
00026d40  // 
00026d40  // Manages BLE advertising state transitions and behavior.
00026d40  // 
00026d40  // Event handling:
00026d40  // - BLE_GAP_EVT_CONNECTED (0x10): Stop advertising, store conn handle
00026d40  // - BLE_GAP_EVT_DISCONNECTED (0x11): Restart advertising based on
00026d40  // mode
00026d40  // - BLE_GAP_EVT_ADV_SET_TERMINATED (0x29): Handle advertising timeout
00026d40  // - BLE_GAP_EVT_TIMEOUT (0x16): Transition advertising modes
00026d40  // 
00026d40  // Advertising modes:
00026d40  // - Fast advertising: 20ms-30ms interval, 180s timeout
00026d40  // - Slow advertising: 1000ms-1285ms interval, no timeout
00026d40  // - Directed advertising: high duty cycle, 1.28s timeout
00026d40  // 
00026d40  // Parameters:
00026d40  // - arg1: ble_evt_t* event structure
00026d40  // 
00026d40  // Advertising state stored at: data_20003b00
00026d40  08b5       push    {r3, lr} {var_4} {__saved_r3}
00026d42  0346       mov     r3, r0
00026d44  0846       mov     r0, r1
00026d46  1a88       ldrh    r2, [r3]
00026d48  112a       cmp     r2, #0x11
00026d4a  08d0       beq     #0x26d5e

00026d4c  1b2a       cmp     r2, #0x1b
00026d4e  0ad0       beq     #0x26d66

00026d50  102a       cmp     r2, #0x10
00026d52  00d0       beq     #0x26d56

00026d54  08bd       pop     {r3, pc} {__saved_r3} {var_4}

00026d56  1946       mov     r1, r3
00026d58  fff702fe   bl      #ble_conn_handle_store
00026d5c  fae7       b       #0x26d54

00026d5e  1946       mov     r1, r3
00026d60  fff7c3ff   bl      #ble_advertising_on_ble_disconnect
00026d64  f6e7       b       #0x26d54

00026d66  1946       mov     r1, r3
00026d68  fff7d8ff   bl      #ble_advertising_on_timeout
00026d6c  f2e7       b       #0x26d54

00026d9c    int32_t sd_ble_gap_disconnect()

00026d9c  // Disconnect from BLE peer
00026d9c  // SDK: components/softdevice/s132/headers/ble_gap.h
00026d9c  // 
00026d9c  // Initiates disconnection from connected BLE peer.
00026d9c  // 
00026d9c  // SVC call: Supervisor Call to SoftDevice (SVC number 0x71)
00026d9c  // Parameters:
00026d9c  // - conn_handle: Connection handle to disconnect
00026d9c  // - hci_status_code: HCI disconnect reason
00026d9c  // 
00026d9c  // HCI disconnect reasons (common):
00026d9c  // - 0x13: BLE_HCI_REMOTE_USER_TERMINATED_CONNECTION
00026d9c  // - 0x14: BLE_HCI_REMOTE_DEV_TERMINATION_DUE_TO_LOW_RESOURCES
00026d9c  // - 0x15: BLE_HCI_REMOTE_DEV_TERMINATION_DUE_TO_POWER_OFF
00026d9c  // - 0x3B: BLE_HCI_LOCAL_HOST_TERMINATED_CONNECTION
00026d9c  // 
00026d9c  // Disconnect sequence:
00026d9c  // 1. Call sd_ble_gap_disconnect(conn_handle, reason)
00026d9c  // 2. SoftDevice sends LL_TERMINATE_IND to peer
00026d9c  // 3. Wait for peer acknowledgment or timeout
00026d9c  // 4. BLE_GAP_EVT_DISCONNECTED event dispatched
00026d9c  // 5. Connection resources freed
00026d9c  // 
00026d9c  // Event data (BLE_GAP_EVT_DISCONNECTED):
00026d9c  // - conn_handle: Handle that was disconnected
00026d9c  // - reason: Disconnect reason code
00026d9c  // - advertising restarts if configured
00026d9c  // 
00026d9c  // Use cases:
00026d9c  // - User initiates disconnect from phone app
00026d9c  // - Inactivity timeout (no communication for N minutes)
00026d9c  // - Security failure (pairing rejected, authentication failed)
00026d9c  // - Device entering sleep mode
00026d9c  // - Firmware update preparation
00026d9c  // 
00026d9c  // Returns: 0 on success, NRF_ERROR_INVALID_CONN_HANDLE if invalid
00026d9c  // handle
00026d9c  90df       svc     #0x90
00026d9e  7047       bx      lr

00026da0  // Reply to security parameter request. Sends security parameters in
00026da0  // response to pairing request from central. SoftDevice S132 v5.1.0
00026da0  // API function.
00026da0  9edf       svc     #0x9e
00026da2  7047       bx      lr

00026de8    void ble_conn_handle_sec_params_request(int16_t* arg1, void* arg2)

00026de8  // Handle BLE security parameters request
00026de8  // SDK: Application-specific security handler
00026de8  // 
00026de8  // Processes BLE_GAP_EVT_SEC_PARAMS_REQUEST from central device.
00026de8  // 
00026de8  // Event: BLE_GAP_EVT_SEC_PARAMS_REQUEST (0x13)
00026de8  // - Central requests pairing/bonding
00026de8  // - Peripheral (this device) must reply with security parameters
00026de8  // 
00026de8  // Security parameters reply:
00026de8  // - Call sd_ble_gap_sec_params_reply() with local security config
00026de8  // - Security params structure (ble_gap_sec_params_t):
00026de8  //   * bond: 1 (enable bonding, save keys)
00026de8  //   * mitm: 1 (Man-In-The-Middle protection, passkey required)
00026de8  //   * lesc: 0/1 (LE Secure Connections P-256 ECDH)
00026de8  //   * keypress: 0 (keypress notifications disabled)
00026de8  //   * io_caps: BLE_GAP_IO_CAPS_NONE (Just Works pairing)
00026de8  //   * oob: 0 (no Out-Of-Band data)
00026de8  //   * min_key_size: 7 bytes
00026de8  //   * max_key_size: 16 bytes
00026de8  //   * kdist_own: Own key distribution (LTK, IRK, CSRK)
00026de8  //   * kdist_peer: Peer key distribution
00026de8  // 
00026de8  // Security configuration source:
00026de8  // - Stored at: data_20003d80 (security_params structure)
00026de8  // - Configured in: ble_conn_init_sec_params_for_connection()
00026de8  // - Defaults from: SDK examples or app requirements
00026de8  // 
00026de8  // Pairing flow after reply:
00026de8  // 1. sd_ble_gap_sec_params_reply() called
00026de8  // 2. SoftDevice negotiates pairing method
00026de8  // 3. BLE_GAP_EVT_PASSKEY_DISPLAY or BLE_GAP_EVT_AUTH_KEY_REQUEST
00026de8  // 4. BLE_GAP_EVT_AUTH_STATUS (success/failure)
00026de8  // 5. On success: Keys exchanged, peer manager stores to FDS
00026de8  // 
00026de8  // Parameters:
00026de8  // - arg1: ble_evt_t* containing SEC_PARAMS_REQUEST event
00026de8  // 
00026de8  // Called from: pm_on_ble_evt() security event handler
00026de8  38b5       push    {r3, r4, r5, lr}
00026dea  0446       mov     r4, r0
00026dec  8d88       ldrh    r5, [r1, #4]
00026dee  0279       ldrb    r2, [r0, #4]
00026df0  00ebc503   add     r3, r0, r5, lsl #3
00026df4  1a73       strb    r2, [r3, #0xc]
00026df6  cb7b       ldrb    r3, [r1, #0xf]
00026df8  012b       cmp     r3, #1
00026dfa  0ed0       beq     #0x26e1a

00026dfc  022b       cmp     r3, #2
00026dfe  11d0       beq     #0x26e24

00026e00  04ebc503   add     r3, r4, r5, lsl #3
00026e04  d988       ldrh    r1, [r3, #6]
00026e06  1b89       ldrh    r3, [r3, #8]
00026e08  9942       cmp     r1, r3
00026e0a  10d8       bhi     #0x26e2e

00026e0c  04ebc503   add     r3, r4, r5, lsl #3
00026e10  1a7b       ldrb    r2, [r3, #0xc]
00026e12  5b7b       ldrb    r3, [r3, #0xd]
00026e14  9a42       cmp     r2, r3
00026e16  1ad8       bhi     #0x26e4e

00026e18  38bd       pop     {r3, r4, r5, pc}

00026e1a  0288       ldrh    r2, [r0]

00026e20  da80       strh    r2, [r3, #6]
00026e22  ede7       b       #0x26e00

00026f02    int32_t ble_conn_handle_sec_info_request(void* arg1, void* arg2)

00026f02  // Handle BLE security info request
00026f02  // SDK: Application-specific security handler
00026f02  // 
00026f02  // Processes BLE_GAP_EVT_SEC_INFO_REQUEST for encrypted reconnection.
00026f02  // 
00026f02  // Event: BLE_GAP_EVT_SEC_INFO_REQUEST (0x14)
00026f02  // - Occurs when bonded peer attempts to reconnect
00026f02  // - Central provides master identification (EDIV, RAND)
00026f02  // - Peripheral must provide LTK (Long Term Key) or reject
00026f02  // 
00026f02  // Security info request handling:
00026f02  // 1. Extract master_id from event (EDIV + RAND)
00026f02  // 2. Call pm_peer_id_get() to find peer by master_id
00026f02  // 3. If peer found:
00026f02  //    - Call pm_peer_data_read() for PM_PEER_DATA_ID_BONDING
00026f02  //    - Extract LTK from bonding data
00026f02  //    - Call sd_ble_gap_sec_info_reply() with LTK
00026f02  // 4. If peer not found:
00026f02  //    - Call sd_ble_gap_sec_info_reply() with NULL (reject)
00026f02  //    - Central will retry with full pairing
00026f02  // 
00026f02  // Bonding keys (pm_peer_data_bonding_t):
00026f02  // - own_ltk: Own Long Term Key (encryption)
00026f02  // - peer_ltk: Peer Long Term Key
00026f02  // - peer_id: Peer Identity Resolving Key (IRK)
00026f02  // - peer_sign: Peer Connection Signature Resolving Key (CSRK)
00026f02  // 
00026f02  // Encrypted reconnection flow:
00026f02  // 1. BLE_GAP_EVT_CONNECTED
00026f02  // 2. BLE_GAP_EVT_SEC_INFO_REQUEST
00026f02  // 3. Reply with LTK
00026f02  // 4. BLE_GAP_EVT_CONN_SEC_UPDATE (encryption enabled)
00026f02  // 5. Resume normal operation
00026f02  // 
00026f02  // Parameters:
00026f02  // - arg1: ble_evt_t* containing SEC_INFO_REQUEST event
00026f02  // 
00026f02  // Called from: pm_on_ble_evt() security event handler
00026f02  10b5       push    {r4, lr} {var_4} {__saved_r4}
00026f04  90b0       sub     sp, #0x40
00026f06  0446       mov     r4, r0
00026f08  0df10c0e   add     lr, sp, #0xc
00026f0c  01f1040c   add     r12, r1, #4
00026f10  bce80f00   ldm     r12!, {r0, r1, r2, r3}
00026f14  aee80f00   stm     lr!, {r0, r1, r2, r3} {var_3c} {var_38} {var_34} {var_30}
00026f18  bce80f00   ldm     r12!, {r0, r1, r2, r3}
00026f1c  aee80f00   stm     lr!, {r0, r1, r2, r3} {var_2c} {var_28} {var_24} {var_20}
00026f20  bce80f00   ldm     r12!, {r0, r1, r2, r3}
00026f24  aee80f00   stm     lr!, {r0, r1, r2, r3} {result_1} {var_18} {var_14} {var_10}
00026f28  dcf80030   ldr     r3, [r12]
00026f2c  cef80030   str     r3, [lr] {var_c}
00026f30  bdf80c10   ldrh    r1, [sp, #0xc] {var_3c}
00026f34  9df81020   ldrb    r2, [sp, #0x10] {var_38}
00026f38  04ebc103   add     r3, r4, r1, lsl #3
00026f3c  5a73       strb    r2, [r3, #0xd]
00026f3e  2369       ldr     r3, [r4, #0x10]
00026f40  73b1       cbz     r3, #0x26f60

00026f42  0020       movs    r0, #0
00026f44  0190       str     r0, [sp, #4] {var_44}  {0x0}
00026f46  adf80800   strh    r0, [sp, #8] {var_40_1}  {0x0}
00026f4a  4df67a20   movw    r0, #0xda7a
00026f4e  adf80400   strh    r0, [sp, #4] {var_44}  {0xda7a}
00026f52  adf80610   strh    r1, [sp, #6] {var_44+0x2}
00026f56  8df80820   strb    r2, [sp, #8] {var_40_1}
00026f5a  01a9       add     r1, sp, #4 {var_44}
00026f5c  2046       mov     r0, r4

00027060    int32_t sd_ble_gatts_characteristic_add()

00027060  // Add GATT characteristic to service
00027060  // SDK: components/softdevice/s132/headers/ble_gatts.h
00027060  // 
00027060  // Adds a characteristic to an existing GATT service.
00027060  // 
00027060  // SVC call: Supervisor Call to SoftDevice (SVC number 0x94)
00027060  // Parameters:
00027060  // - service_handle: Handle of parent service
00027060  // - char_md: Characteristic metadata (properties, descriptors)
00027060  // - attr_char_value: Characteristic value attribute (UUID,
00027060  // permissions, value)
00027060  // - handles: Output structure with allocated handles
00027060  // 
00027060  // Characteristic properties (char_md.char_props):
00027060  // - broadcast: 0x01
00027060  // - read: 0x02
00027060  // - write_wo_resp: 0x04
00027060  // - write: 0x08
00027060  // - notify: 0x10
00027060  // - indicate: 0x20
00027060  // - auth_signed_wr: 0x40
00027060  // 
00027060  // Attribute permissions (attr_char_value.init_len, max_len, p_value):
00027060  // - read_perm: Security level (open, encrypted, MITM)
00027060  // - write_perm: Security level (open, encrypted, MITM)
00027060  // - vlen: Variable length flag
00027060  // - vloc: Value location (stack, user memory)
00027060  // 
00027060  // Handles allocated (output):
00027060  // - value_handle: Characteristic value handle
00027060  // - user_desc_handle: User description descriptor (if configured)
00027060  // - cccd_handle: Client Characteristic Configuration Descriptor (if
00027060  // notify/indicate)
00027060  // - sccd_handle: Server Characteristic Configuration Descriptor (if
00027060  // broadcast)
00027060  // 
00027060  // Returns: 0 on success, NRF_ERROR_INVALID_PARAM if invalid config
00027060  a2df       svc     #0xa2
00027062  7047       bx      lr

00027fc8    int32_t fds_delete_op_state_machine(int32_t arg1, void* arg2)

00027fc8  // FDS record deletion state machine
00027fc8  // SDK: components/libraries/fds/fds_internal_defs.h
00027fc8  // 
00027fc8  // State machine for deleting FDS records with SoftDevice
00027fc8  // coordination.
00027fc8  // 
00027fc8  // States:
00027fc8  // 0: Idle - no operation pending
00027fc8  // 1: Find record - locate by file_id/record_key
00027fc8  // 2: Mark deleted - set record header flag to 0xffff (deleted marker)
00027fc8  // 3: Write header - commit deletion marker to flash via fstorage
00027fc8  // 4: Wait fstorage - block until SoftDevice completes flash write
00027fc8  // 5: Update tables - remove from internal file ID table
00027fc8  // 6: Dispatch event - send FDS_EVT_DEL_RECORD to callbacks
00027fc8  // 7: Complete - return to idle
00027fc8  // 
00027fc8  // Record lookup: fds_find_by_descriptor()
00027fc8  // Flash write: fstorage_write() via SoftDevice
00027fc8  // Callbacks: fds_app_evt_handler(), app_fds_evt_handler()
00027fc8  // 
00027fc8  // Parameters stored at: data_20003c00 (operation context)
00027fc8  // Returns: Next state or 0 (idle) on completion
00027fc8  b0b9       cbnz    r0, #0x27ff8

00027fca  08b5       push    {r3, lr}
00027fcc  0b79       ldrb    r3, [r1, #4]
00027fce  012b       cmp     r3, #1
00027fd0  0ad0       beq     #0x27fe8

00027fd2  022b       cmp     r3, #2
00027fd4  12d0       beq     #0x27ffc

00027fd6  0bb1       cbz     r3, #0x27fdc

00027fd8  0f20       movs    r0, #0xf

00027fda  08bd       pop     {r3, pc}

00027fdc  0223       movs    r3, #2
00027fde  0b71       strb    r3, [r1, #4]
00027fe0  0846       mov     r0, r1
00027fe2  fff7b9ff   bl      #0x27f58
00027fe6  f8e7       b       #0x27fda

00027fe8  0846       mov     r0, r1
00027fea  fff7d1ff   bl      #0x27f90
00027fee  0a28       cmp     r0, #0xa
00027ff0  f3d1       bne     #0x27fda

0002808c    int32_t fds_gc_dispatcher(int32_t arg1, int32_t arg2)

0002808c  // FDS garbage collection dispatcher/coordinator
0002808c  // SDK: components/libraries/fds/fds.c
0002808c  // 
0002808c  // Coordinates multi-stage garbage collection process.
0002808c  // Dispatches to appropriate handler for each GC phase.
0002808c  // 
0002808c  // GC phases coordinated:
0002808c  // 1. Select source page: Choose page with most deleted records
0002808c  // 2. Prepare swap page: Ensure destination page is erased
0002808c  // 3. Copy valid records: Transfer active records to swap page
0002808c  // 4. Verify copies: Confirm all data transferred correctly
0002808c  // 5. Erase source page: Call fds_gc_page_erase() for old page
0002808c  // 6. Update metadata: Adjust page headers, statistics
0002808c  // 7. Finalize: Update internal tables, dispatch FDS_EVT_GC
0002808c  // 
0002808c  // State stored at: data_20003c40 (gc_state structure)
0002808c  // - gc_state: Current phase (0-7)
0002808c  // - source_page: Page being garbage collected
0002808c  // - dest_page: Swap page receiving valid records
0002808c  // - records_copied: Counter for progress tracking
0002808c  // 
0002808c  // Called from: fds_gc() and periodic maintenance tasks
0002808c  // 
0002808c  // Dispatches event: FDS_EVT_GC on completion (success/failure)
0002808c  30bb       cbnz    r0, #0x280dc

0002808e  08b5       push    {r3, lr}
00028090  144b       ldr     r3, [pc, #0x50]
00028092  1b7b       ldrb    r3, [r3, #0xc]
00028094  6bb1       cbz     r3, #0x280b2

00028096  134b       ldr     r3, [pc, #0x4c]
00028098  0022       movs    r2, #0
0002809a  1a73       strb    r2, [r3, #0xc]

0002809c  114b       ldr     r3, [pc, #0x44]
0002809e  1b78       ldrb    r3, [r3]
000280a0  013b       subs    r3, #1
000280a2  062b       cmp     r3, #6
000280a4  1cd8       bhi     #0x280e0

000280a6  dfe803f0   tbb     [pc, r3]

{Case 0x0}

000281e8    int32_t fds_flash_init()

000281e8  // Initialize FDS flash storage subsystem
000281e8  // SDK: components/libraries/fds/fds.c
000281e8  // 
000281e8  // Initializes Flash Data Storage filesystem for persistent data.
000281e8  // Scans flash pages for existing records, builds internal tables.
000281e8  // 
000281e8  // Initialization sequence:
000281e8  // 1. Set flash bounds with fds_flash_bounds_set()
000281e8  // 2. Scan pages for record headers and compute statistics
000281e8  // 3. Build file ID tables and free space maps
000281e8  // 4. Register fstorage callback for SoftDevice flash operations
000281e8  // 5. Dispatch FDS_EVT_INIT event on completion
000281e8  // 
000281e8  // Flash layout:
000281e8  // - 2+ pages reserved for FDS (typically 4KB each on nRF52832)
000281e8  // - Page header: magic number, erase count
000281e8  // - Records: header (file_id, record_key, length_words) + data
000281e8  // 
000281e8  // Parameters:
000281e8  // - None (uses static configuration)
000281e8  // 
000281e8  // Returns: 0 (NRF_SUCCESS) on success
000281e8  // Dispatches: FDS_EVT_INIT to registered callbacks
000281e8  08b5       push    {r3, lr}
000281ea  fff7d3fc   bl      #0x27b94
000281ee  0022       movs    r2, #0
000281f0  0249       ldr     r1, [pc, #8]
000281f2  0348       ldr     r0, [pc, #0xc]
000281f4  00f07efa   bl      #0x286f4
000281f8  08bd       pop     {r3, pc}

000281fa                                                                                00 bf                                        ..

000281fc  void* data_281fc = data_3a05c
00028200  int32_t data_28200 = 0x20003510

000285d8    int32_t fds_gc(int32_t arg1)

000285d8  // Trigger FDS garbage collection
000285d8  // SDK: components/libraries/fds/fds.c
000285d8  // 
000285d8  // Initiates garbage collection to reclaim space from deleted records.
000285d8  // Copies valid records to new page, erases old page.
000285d8  // 
000285d8  // GC triggers:
000285d8  // - Explicit call to fds_gc()
000285d8  // - Automatic when write fails due to insufficient space
000285d8  // - After multiple delete operations
000285d8  // 
000285d8  // GC process:
000285d8  // 1. Select page with most deleted records (fds_gc_pending_files)
000285d8  // 2. Copy all valid records to swap page
000285d8  // 3. Erase source page with fds_gc_page_erase()
000285d8  // 4. Update page headers and statistics
000285d8  // 5. Dispatch FDS_EVT_GC event
000285d8  // 
000285d8  // State machine: fds_gc_dispatcher()
000285d8  // - State 0: Idle
000285d8  // - State 1: Copy records
000285d8  // - State 2: Erase page
000285d8  // - State 3: Update headers
000285d8  // - State 4: Complete
000285d8  // 
000285d8  // Returns: 0 on success, NRF_ERROR_BUSY if GC already running
000285d8  104b       ldr     r3, [pc, #0x40]
000285da  1b78       ldrb    r3, [r3]
000285dc  bbb1       cbz     r3, #0x2860e

000285de  10b5       push    {r4, lr}
000285e0  82b0       sub     sp, #8
000285e2  0446       mov     r4, r0
000285e4  4ff6ff73   movw    r3, #0xffff
000285e8  9842       cmp     r0, r3
000285ea  12d0       beq     #0x28612

000285ec  01a8       add     r0, sp, #4
000285ee  fff715fe   bl      #0x2821c
000285f2  80b1       cbz     r0, #0x28616

000285f4  0522       movs    r2, #5
000285f6  0270       strb    r2, [r0]
000285f8  0122       movs    r2, #1
000285fa  0271       strb    r2, [r0, #4]
000285fc  c480       strh    r4, [r0, #6]
000285fe  01a8       add     r0, sp, #4
00028600  fff71afe   bl      #0x28238
00028604  fff7dcfd   bl      #0x281c0
00028608  0020       movs    r0, #0

0002860a  02b0       add     sp, #8
0002860c  10bd       pop     {r4, pc}

0002860e  0220       movs    r0, #2
00028610  7047       bx      lr

00028612  0420       movs    r0, #4
00028614  f9e7       b       #0x2860a

00028616  0820       movs    r0, #8
00028618  f7e7       b       #0x2860a

0002861a                                                                                00 bf                                        ..

0002861c  void* data_2861c = data_200038e8

000286b8    int32_t fds_descriptor_from_rec_id(int32_t* arg1, int32_t* arg2)

000286b8  // Convert record ID to FDS descriptor
000286b8  // SDK: components/libraries/fds/fds.c
000286b8  // 
000286b8  // Converts external record ID (uint32_t handle) to internal
000286b8  // fds_record_desc_t descriptor for record operations.
000286b8  // 
000286b8  // FDS descriptor structure:
000286b8  // - record_id: Unique record identifier (increments)
000286b8  // - p_record: Pointer to record header in flash
000286b8  // - gc_run_count: GC count when record was created (validation)
000286b8  // 
000286b8  // Record ID encoding:
000286b8  // - Upper 16 bits: GC run count (ensures validity after GC)
000286b8  // - Lower 16 bits: Sequential record number
000286b8  // 
000286b8  // Use cases:
000286b8  // - fds_record_find() -> descriptor -> fds_record_open()
000286b8  // - fds_record_update() needs descriptor for target record
000286b8  // - fds_record_delete() uses descriptor to locate record
000286b8  // 
000286b8  // Parameters:
000286b8  // - arg1: fds_record_desc_t* output descriptor
000286b8  // - arg2: uint32_t record_id (external handle)
000286b8  // 
000286b8  // Returns: 0 on success, NRF_ERROR_NOT_FOUND if invalid
000286b8  20b1       cbz     r0, #0x286c4

000286ba  29b1       cbz     r1, #0x286c8

000286bc  0368       ldr     r3, [r0]
000286be  0b60       str     r3, [r1]
000286c0  0020       movs    r0, #0
000286c2  7047       bx      lr

000286c4  0520       movs    r0, #5
000286c6  7047       bx      lr

000286c8  0520       movs    r0, #5
000286ca  7047       bx      lr
