00028ed4    int32_t* ble_gatts_write_evt_handler(char* arg1)

00028ed4  // Handle GATT write events from BLE peer
00028ed4  // SDK: Application-specific GATT event handler
00028ed4  // 
00028ed4  // Processes BLE_GATTS_EVT_WRITE events for characteristic writes.
00028ed4  // 
00028ed4  // Write event structure (ble_gatts_evt_write_t):
00028ed4  // - handle: Attribute handle being written
00028ed4  // - uuid: UUID of characteristic
00028ed4  // - op: Write operation type (write, write_no_resp, prepare_write)
00028ed4  // - auth_required: Whether authentication required
00028ed4  // - offset: Offset for long writes
00028ed4  // - len: Data length
00028ed4  // - data: Written data bytes
00028ed4  // 
00028ed4  // Write operations:
00028ed4  // - BLE_GATTS_OP_WRITE_REQ (0x01): Write with response
00028ed4  // - BLE_GATTS_OP_WRITE_CMD (0x02): Write without response
00028ed4  // - BLE_GATTS_OP_EXEC_WRITE_REQ_NOW (0x04): Execute prepared writes
00028ed4  // 
00028ed4  // Common write targets:
00028ed4  // - CCCD handles: Enable/disable notifications/indications
00028ed4  // - Control characteristics: Mode changes, settings updates
00028ed4  // - Configuration characteristics: Device parameters
00028ed4  // - Command characteristics: Execute operations
00028ed4  // 
00028ed4  // Write handling:
00028ed4  // 1. Extract handle from ble_gatts_evt_write_t
00028ed4  // 2. Map handle to characteristic (compare against known handles)
00028ed4  // 3. Validate data length and format
00028ed4  // 4. Process write based on characteristic:
00028ed4  //    - CCCD: Update notification state
00028ed4  //    - Control: Execute mode/setting change
00028ed4  //    - Config: Update device parameters
00028ed4  // 5. Send response if BLE_GATTS_OP_WRITE_REQ
00028ed4  // 
00028ed4  // Parameters:
00028ed4  // - arg1: ble_evt_t* containing GATTS write event
00028ed4  // 
00028ed4  // Called from: ble_evt_router on BLE_GATTS_EVT_WRITE (0x33)
00028ed4  10b5       push    {r4, lr}
00028ed6  82b0       sub     sp, #8
00028ed8  0378       ldrb    r3, [r0]
00028eda  082b       cmp     r3, #8
00028edc  05d0       beq     #0x28eea

00028ede  1f4b       ldr     r3, [pc, #0x7c]
00028ee0  1878       ldrb    r0, [r3]
00028ee2  fff791ff   bl      #0x28e08
00028ee6  02b0       add     sp, #8
00028ee8  10bd       pop     {r4, pc}

00028eea  0446       mov     r4, r0

00028eee  002b       cmp     r3, #0
00028ef0  f5d1       bne     #0x28ede

000290d8  int32_t data_290d8 = 0x20003aa7

000290dc    int32_t sd_ble_gatts_sys_attr_set()

000290dc  // Restore GATT system attributes for bonded peer
000290dc  // SDK: components/softdevice/s132/headers/ble_gatts.h
000290dc  // 
000290dc  // Restores system attributes (CCCD, SCCD) for reconnecting bonded
000290dc  // peer.
000290dc  // 
000290dc  // SVC call: Supervisor Call to SoftDevice (SVC number 0x9C)
000290dc  // Parameters:
000290dc  // - conn_handle: Connection handle for peer
000290dc  // - p_sys_attr_data: Pointer to saved system attributes
000290dc  // - len: Length of system attribute data
000290dc  // - flags: Reserved (must be 0)
000290dc  // 
000290dc  // System attributes:
000290dc  // - CCCD (Client Characteristic Configuration Descriptor):
000290dc  //   * Notifications enabled: 0x0001
000290dc  //   * Indications enabled: 0x0002
000290dc  //   * Both enabled: 0x0003
000290dc  //   * Disabled: 0x0000
000290dc  // - SCCD (Server Characteristic Configuration Descriptor):
000290dc  //   * Broadcast enabled: 0x0001
000290dc  // 
000290dc  // Restoration sequence:
000290dc  // 1. BLE_GAP_EVT_CONNECTED received
000290dc  // 2. Look up peer_id from connection handle (Peer Manager)
000290dc  // 3. Read PM_PEER_DATA_ID_GATT_LOCAL from FDS
000290dc  // 4. Call sd_ble_gatts_sys_attr_set() with saved data
000290dc  // 5. SoftDevice applies CCCD/SCCD values to characteristics
000290dc  // 
000290dc  // If no data (new peer or fresh bond):
000290dc  // - Call with p_sys_attr_data = NULL, len = 0
000290dc  // - Resets all CCCDs to default (disabled)
000290dc  // 
000290dc  // Called from:
000290dc  // - pm_on_ble_evt() in response to BLE_GATTS_EVT_SYS_ATTR_MISSING
000290dc  // - Prevents notification failures after reconnection
000290dc  // 
000290dc  // Returns: 0 on success, NRF_ERROR_INVALID_STATE if no connection
000290dc  a7df       svc     #0xa7
000290de  7047       bx      lr


000290e0    int32_t sd_ble_gatts_value_get()

000290e0  a9df       svc     #0xa9
000290e2  7047       bx      lr


000290e4    int32_t sd_ble_gatts_value_set()

000290e4  // Set GATT characteristic value. Updates characteristic value in
000290e4  // attribute table. SoftDevice S132 v5.1.0 API function.
000290e4  aadf       svc     #0xaa
000290e6  7047       bx      lr


000290e8    int32_t sd_ble_gatts_hvx()

000290e8  // Send GATT notification or indication
000290e8  // SDK: components/softdevice/s132/headers/ble_gatts.h
000290e8  // 
000290e8  // Sends Handle Value Notification or Indication to connected peer.
000290e8  // 
000290e8  // SVC call: Supervisor Call to SoftDevice (SVC number 0x99)
000290e8  // Parameters:
000290e8  // - conn_handle: Connection to send notification/indication
000290e8  // - hvx_params: Notification/indication parameters structure
000290e8  // 
000290e8  // HVX parameters (ble_gatts_hvx_params_t):
000290e8  // - handle: Characteristic value handle
000290e8  // - type: BLE_GATT_HVX_NOTIFICATION (0x01) or BLE_GATT_HVX_INDICATION
000290e8  // (0x02)
000290e8  // - offset: Offset in characteristic value (for long values)
000290e8  // - p_len: Pointer to data length (in/out, may be reduced if MTU
000290e8  // insufficient)
000290e8  // - p_data: Pointer to data to send
000290e8  // 
000290e8  // Notification vs Indication:
000290e8  // - Notification: No acknowledgment, fire-and-forget, lower latency
000290e8  // - Indication: Requires peer confirmation, guaranteed delivery,
000290e8  // higher latency
000290e8  // 
000290e8  // MTU handling:
000290e8  // - Default MTU: 23 bytes (20 bytes payload after 3-byte header)
000290e8  // - MTU exchange: Can negotiate up to 247 bytes via
000290e8  // BLE_GATTC_EVT_EXCHANGE_MTU_RSP
000290e8  // - If data length > (MTU - 3), SoftDevice truncates and updates
000290e8  // p_len
000290e8  // 
000290e8  // Use cases:
000290e8  // - Battery level updates (notification)
000290e8  // - Sensor readings (notification)
000290e8  // - CAN message forwarding to phone app (notification)
000290e8  // - Critical configuration changes (indication for reliability)
000290e8  // 
000290e8  // Flow control: Only 1 indication can be pending per connection
000290e8  // - Must wait for BLE_GATTS_EVT_HVC before sending next indication
000290e8  // 
000290e8  // Returns: 0 on success, NRF_ERROR_RESOURCES if queue full
000290e8  abdf       svc     #0xab
000290ea  7047       bx      lr

00029304    int32_t ble_hvx_send_with_retry()

00029304  // Send BLE Handle Value Notification/Indication with automatic retry.
00029304  // Calls sd_ble_gatts_hvx (SoftDevice GATT server API).
00029304  // Returns 3 if immediate failure, else retries on 0x3003
00029304  // (NRF_ERROR_RESOURCES).
00029304  // Increments data_20003aae retry counter on each 0x3003 error.
00029304  // Loops until success or different error code.
00029304  // Handles BLE stack busy condition during characteristic
00029304  // notifications.
00029304  // From BLE GATT server notification implementation.
00029304  10b5       push    {r4, lr}
00029306  0446       mov     r4, r0
00029308  0c48       ldr     r0, [pc, #0x30]
0002930a  fff7edfe   bl      #0x290e8
0002930e  28b1       cbz     r0, #0x2931c

00029310  0320       movs    r0, #3

00029312  10bd       pop     {r4, pc}

00029314  43f20303   movw    r3, #0x3003
00029318  9842       cmp     r0, r3
0002931a  fad1       bne     #0x29312

0002931c  4ff6ff72   movw    r2, #0xffff
00029320  064b       ldr     r3, [pc, #0x18]
00029322  1988       ldrh    r1, [r3]
00029324  2046       mov     r0, r4
00029326  fff7d9fe   bl      #0x290dc
0002932a  43f20303   movw    r3, #0x3003
0002932e  9842       cmp     r0, r3
00029330  f0d1       bne     #0x29314

00029332  024a       ldr     r2, [pc, #8]
00029334  1388       ldrh    r3, [r2]
00029336  0133       adds    r3, #1
00029338  1380       strh    r3, [r2]
0002933a  ebe7       b       #0x29314

0002933c  void* data_2933c = data_20003aae

00029428    uint32_t ble_conn_table_set_data(int32_t arg1, int16_t arg2)

00029428  // Store data in BLE connection table by connection handle.
00029428  // Finds connection slot via ble_conn_table_find_slot_by_conn.
00029428  // Slot index * 3 gives table offset, stores arg2 at data_20003ab4 +
00029428  // offset.

00029428  // Connection table tracks per-connection state and handles.

000294f6    int32_t uuid_struct_compare(void* arg1, void* arg2)

0002971e    int32_t ble_gap_disconnect_with_transform(char* arg1, char* arg2, char* arg3)

0002971e  // Application: Reverses 16-byte array from arg1, zeroes 13 bytes,
0002971e  // copies 3 bytes from arg2, calls sd_ble_gap_disconnect, copies 3
0002971e  // bytes to arg3 (likely crypto/encoding operation)
0002971e  30b5       push    {r4, r5, lr}
00029720  8db0       sub     sp, #0x34
00029722  0d46       mov     r5, r1
00029724  1446       mov     r4, r2

0002a15c    int32_t app_fds_evt_handler(char* arg1)

0002a15c  // Application FDS event callback handler
0002a15c  // SDK: Application-specific (main.c or similar)
0002a15c  // 
0002a15c  // Handles FDS events dispatched from flash operations.
0002a15c  // 
0002a15c  // Events handled:
0002a15c  // - FDS_EVT_INIT (0): FDS initialization complete
0002a15c  // - FDS_EVT_WRITE (1): Record write completed
0002a15c  // - FDS_EVT_UPDATE (2): Record update completed
0002a15c  // - FDS_EVT_DEL_RECORD (3): Record deletion completed
0002a15c  // - FDS_EVT_DEL_FILE (4): File (all records with file_id) deleted
0002a15c  // - FDS_EVT_GC (5): Garbage collection completed
0002a15c  // 
0002a15c  // Event structure (fds_evt_t):
0002a15c  // - id: Event type (0-5)
0002a15c  // - result: Operation result (NRF_SUCCESS or error)
0002a15c  // - file_id: File ID affected
0002a15c  // - record_key: Record key affected
0002a15c  // - record_id: Record ID for write/update operations
0002a15c  // 
0002a15c  // Application actions:
0002a15c  // - Update UI on successful writes
0002a15c  // - Retry operations on errors
0002a15c  // - Trigger dependent operations after GC
0002a15c  // - Log errors for debugging
0002a15c  // 
0002a15c  // Parameters:
0002a15c  // - arg1: fds_evt_t const* event structure
0002a15c  38b5       push    {r3, r4, r5, lr}
0002a15e  0446       mov     r4, r0
0002a160  c068       ldr     r0, [r0, #0xc]
0002a162  fff7cffe   bl      #0x29f04
0002a166  2378       ldrb    r3, [r4]
0002a168  092b       cmp     r3, #9
0002a16a  12d0       beq     #0x2a192

0002a16c  132b       cmp     r3, #0x13
0002a16e  1ed0       beq     #0x2a1ae

0002a170  082b       cmp     r3, #8
0002a172  07d0       beq     #0x2a184

0002a174  0025       movs    r5, #0

0002a176  2046       mov     r0, r4
0002a178  fff7eefe   bl      #0x29f58

0002a17c  2846       mov     r0, r5
0002a17e  fff7c7ff   bl      #0x2a110
0002a182  38bd       pop     {r3, r4, r5, pc}

0002a184  637a       ldrb    r3, [r4, #9]
0002a186  a3b9       cbnz    r3, #0x2a1b2

0002a188  a8b1       cbz     r0, #0x2a1b6

0002a18a  fff72bff   bl      #0x29fe4

0002a3a8    int32_t app_context_record_reserve(int32_t arg1, int32_t arg2)

0002a3a8  // Application: Reserves space for app context record, validates key
0002a3a8  // 7/8, finds context with app_context_find_available, returns 0 if
0002a3a8  // already has reservation, gets buffer with sub_2abf8, prepares
0002a3a8  // header with
0002a3a8  // fds_record_prepare_header_wrapper/fds_record_calculate_length,
0002a3a8  // reserves with fds_wrapper_reserve, converts error 9 to 3

0002a568    uint32_t bitmask_find_next_set_bit(int32_t arg1, int32_t arg2)

0002a568  // Find next set bit in bitmask after given position.
0002a568  // Starts at arg1+1 (or 0 if arg1==0xffff), checks up to bit 255.
0002a568  // Calls bitmask_is_null_or_bit_set to test each bit.
0002a568  // Returns bit position if found, 0xffff if no more set bits.
0002a568  // Used for iterating through multi-word bitmasks.
0002a568  38b5       push    {r3, r4, r5, lr}
0002a56a  0d46       mov     r5, r1
0002a56c  4ff6ff73   movw    r3, #0xffff
0002a570  9842       cmp     r0, r3
0002a572  02d0       beq     #0x2a57a

0002a574  441c       adds    r4, r0, #1
0002a576  a4b2       uxth    r4, r4
0002a578  03e0       b       #0x2a582

0002a57a  0024       movs    r4, #0
0002a57c  01e0       b       #0x2a582

0002a57e  0134       adds    r4, #1
0002a580  a4b2       uxth    r4, r4

0002a582  ff2c       cmp     r4, #0xff
0002a584  06d8       bhi     #0x2a594

0002a586  2146       mov     r1, r4
0002a588  2846       mov     r0, r5
0002a58a  00f001fc   bl      #0x2ad90
0002a58e  0028       cmp     r0, #0
0002a590  f5d0       beq     #0x2a57e

0002a592  01e0       b       #0x2a598

0002a594  4ff6ff74   movw    r4, #0xffff

0002a598  2046       mov     r0, r4
0002a59a  38bd       pop     {r3, r4, r5, pc}

0002a604    int32_t system_state_init()

0002a604  // mode, assist level, brightness, units. Loads saved state from FDS
0002a604  // if available.

0002a606  4ff6ff72   movw    r2, #0xffff
0002a60a  // g_pm_peer_rank @ 0x20003ce8: Initialize peer manager rank to 0xffff
0002a60a  1a80       strh    r2, [r3]
0002a60c  044b       ldr     r3, [pc, #0x10]

0002a628    void pm_on_ble_evt(int16_t* arg1)

0002a628  // Peer Manager BLE event handler
0002a628  // SDK: components/ble/peer_manager/peer_manager.c
0002a628  // 
0002a628  // Main entry point for Peer Manager to handle BLE events.
0002a628  // Manages bonding, pairing, encryption, and peer database.
0002a628  // 
0002a628  // Key events handled:
0002a628  // - BLE_GAP_EVT_CONNECTED (0x10): Lookup/create peer ID
0002a628  // - BLE_GAP_EVT_DISCONNECTED (0x11): Update peer ranking
0002a628  // - BLE_GAP_EVT_SEC_PARAMS_REQUEST (0x13): Send security parameters
0002a628  // - BLE_GAP_EVT_SEC_INFO_REQUEST (0x14): Provide stored keys
0002a628  // - BLE_GAP_EVT_PASSKEY_DISPLAY (0x17): Display passkey for pairing
0002a628  // - BLE_GAP_EVT_AUTH_KEY_REQUEST (0x18): Request passkey input
0002a628  // - BLE_GAP_EVT_AUTH_STATUS (0x19): Handle pairing result
0002a628  // - BLE_GAP_EVT_CONN_SEC_UPDATE (0x1a): Update security level
0002a628  // - BLE_GATTS_EVT_SYS_ATTR_MISSING (0x31): Restore system attributes
0002a628  // 
0002a628  // Parameters:
0002a628  // - arg1: ble_evt_t* event structure
0002a628  // 
0002a628  // Dispatches to: pm_evt_dispatch, pm_evt_handler_connection
0002a628  074b       ldr     r3, [pc, #0x1c]
0002a62a  1b78       ldrb    r3, [r3]
0002a62c  03b9       cbnz    r3, #0x2a630

0002a62e  7047       bx      lr

0002a630  10b5       push    {r4, lr}
0002a632  0446       mov     r4, r0
0002a634  fff7ccf8   bl      #0x297d0
0002a638  2046       mov     r0, r4
0002a63a  01f025fa   bl      #0x2ba88
0002a63e  2046       mov     r0, r4
0002a640  fef7d0fc   bl      #0x28fe4
0002a644  10bd       pop     {r4, pc}

0002a646                    00 bf                                                                                ..

0002a648  int32_t data_2a648 = 0x20003cea

0002a64c    void pm_evt_handler_connection(char* arg1)

0002a64c  // Application: PM connection event handler, if event type 2
0002a64c  // (disconnect) checks if arg1[8]==1, sets slot bitmask
0002a64c  // (data_20003cd0), dispatches callbacks with
0002a64c  // pm_evt_dispatch_callbacks
0002a64c  98b1       cbz     r0, #0x2a676

0002a64e  10b5       push    {r4, lr}
0002a650  0446       mov     r4, r0
0002a652  0378       ldrb    r3, [r0]
0002a654  022b       cmp     r3, #2
0002a656  03d0       beq     #0x2a660

0002a658  2046       mov     r0, r4
0002a65a  fff7bfff   bl      #0x2a5dc
0002a65e  10bd       pop     {r4, pc}

0002a660  027a       ldrb    r2, [r0, #8]
0002a662  012a       cmp     r2, #1
0002a664  14bf       ite     ne
0002a666  0022       movs    r2, #0
0002a668  0122       movs    r2, #1
0002a66a  034b       ldr     r3, [pc, #0xc]
0002a66c  1978       ldrb    r1, [r3]
0002a66e  4088       ldrh    r0, [r0, #2]
0002a670  fbf746fc   bl      #0x25f00
0002a674  f0e7       b       #0x2a658

0002a676  7047       bx      lr

0002a678  int32_t data_2a678 = 0x20003cd0

0002a67c    int32_t pm_evt_dispatch(int32_t arg1)

0002a67c  // Dispatch Peer Manager events to application callbacks
0002a67c  // SDK: components/ble/peer_manager/peer_manager_internal.h
0002a67c  // 
0002a67c  // Central event dispatcher for Peer Manager events.
0002a67c  // Calls all registered PM event handlers with event structure.
0002a67c  // 
0002a67c  // PM event types (pm_evt_id_t):
0002a67c  // - PM_EVT_BONDED_PEER_CONNECTED (0): Previously bonded peer
0002a67c  // connected
0002a67c  // - PM_EVT_CONN_SEC_START (1): Security procedure started
0002a67c  // - PM_EVT_CONN_SEC_SUCCEEDED (2): Encryption/pairing succeeded
0002a67c  // - PM_EVT_CONN_SEC_FAILED (3): Security procedure failed
0002a67c  // - PM_EVT_CONN_SEC_CONFIG_REQ (4): Security config request
0002a67c  // - PM_EVT_STORAGE_FULL (5): Peer database full, delete required
0002a67c  // - PM_EVT_ERROR_UNEXPECTED (6): Unexpected error occurred
0002a67c  // - PM_EVT_PEER_DATA_UPDATE_SUCCEEDED (7): Peer data stored
0002a67c  // - PM_EVT_PEER_DATA_UPDATE_FAILED (8): Peer data storage failed
0002a67c  // - PM_EVT_PEER_DELETE_SUCCEEDED (9): Peer deleted from database
0002a67c  // - PM_EVT_PEER_DELETE_FAILED (10): Peer deletion failed
0002a67c  // - PM_EVT_PEERS_DELETE_SUCCEEDED (11): All peers deleted
0002a67c  // - PM_EVT_PEERS_DELETE_FAILED (12): All peers deletion failed
0002a67c  // 
0002a67c  // Parameters:
0002a67c  // - arg1: pm_evt_t* event structure
0002a67c  // 
0002a67c  // Calls: pm_evt_dispatch_callbacks() to iterate handler list
0002a67c  08b5       push    {r3, lr}
0002a67e  fff7adff   bl      #0x2a5dc
0002a682  08bd       pop     {r3, pc}

0002a770    int32_t pm_peer_data_read(int32_t arg1, int32_t arg2)

0002a770  // Read peer data from persistent storage
0002a770  // SDK: components/ble/peer_manager/peer_database.c
0002a770  // 
0002a770  // Retrieves stored peer data (keys, system attributes) from FDS.
0002a770  // 
0002a770  // Peer data types (pm_peer_data_id_t):
0002a770  // - PM_PEER_DATA_ID_BONDING (0): Bonding keys (IRK, LTK, CSRK)
0002a770  // - PM_PEER_DATA_ID_SERVICE_CHANGED_PENDING (1): GATT service change
0002a770  // flag
0002a770  // - PM_PEER_DATA_ID_GATT_LOCAL (2): Local GATT database hash
0002a770  // - PM_PEER_DATA_ID_GATT_REMOTE (3): Remote GATT database cache
0002a770  // - PM_PEER_DATA_ID_PEER_RANK (4): Peer priority ranking
0002a770  // - PM_PEER_DATA_ID_APPLICATION (5): Application-specific data
0002a770  // 
0002a770  // FDS file structure:
0002a770  // - file_id: Peer ID (unique per bonded device)
0002a770  // - record_key: Data type (0-5 above)
0002a770  // - data: Serialized structure (keys, attributes, etc.)
0002a770  // 
0002a770  // Read process:
0002a770  // 1. Convert peer_id to FDS file_id
0002a770  // 2. Call fds_record_find() with file_id + record_key
0002a770  // 3. Open record with fds_record_open()
0002a770  // 4. Copy data to provided buffer
0002a770  // 5. Close record with fds_record_close()
0002a770  // 
0002a770  // Parameters:
0002a770  // - arg1: pm_peer_id_t peer ID
0002a770  // - arg2: pm_peer_data_id_t data type
0002a770  // - arg3: void* output buffer
0002a770  // - arg4: uint16_t* buffer size (in/out)
0002a770  // 
0002a770  // Returns: 0 on success, NRF_ERROR_NOT_FOUND if no data
0002a770  08b5       push    {r3, lr}
0002a772  044b       ldr     r3, [pc, #0x10]
0002a774  1b78       ldrb    r3, [r3]
0002a776  13b1       cbz     r3, #0x2a77e

0002a778  01f0b4f9   bl      #0x2bae4

0002a77c  08bd       pop     {r3, pc}

0002a77e  0820       movs    r0, #8
0002a780  fce7       b       #0x2a77c

0002a782        00 bf                                                                                        ..

0002a784  void* data_2a784 = data_20003cea

0002a7a8    uint32_t pm_peer_delete(int32_t arg1)

0002a7a8  // Delete peer from bonding database
0002a7a8  // SDK: components/ble/peer_manager/peer_manager.c
0002a7a8  // 
0002a7a8  // Removes all data for a bonded peer from persistent storage.
0002a7a8  // 
0002a7a8  // Deletion process:
0002a7a8  // 1. Validate peer_id exists in database
0002a7a8  // 2. Queue deletion of all data types:
0002a7a8  //    - PM_PEER_DATA_ID_BONDING (keys)
0002a7a8  //    - PM_PEER_DATA_ID_SERVICE_CHANGED_PENDING
0002a7a8  //    - PM_PEER_DATA_ID_GATT_LOCAL
0002a7a8  //    - PM_PEER_DATA_ID_GATT_REMOTE
0002a7a8  //    - PM_PEER_DATA_ID_PEER_RANK
0002a7a8  //    - PM_PEER_DATA_ID_APPLICATION
0002a7a8  // 3. Call fds_record_delete() for each FDS record
0002a7a8  // 4. Update internal peer table at data_20003d00
0002a7a8  // 5. Dispatch PM_EVT_PEER_DELETE_SUCCEEDED on completion
0002a7a8  // 
0002a7a8  // Use cases:
0002a7a8  // - User requests unbonding from UI
0002a7a8  // - Storage full, delete lowest-ranked peer
0002a7a8  // - Security failure, remove compromised peer
0002a7a8  // - Factory reset, delete all peers
0002a7a8  // 
0002a7a8  // Parameters:
0002a7a8  // - arg1: pm_peer_id_t peer ID to delete
0002a7a8  // 
0002a7a8  // Returns: 0 on success, NRF_ERROR_BUSY if operation pending
0002a7a8  // Dispatches: PM_EVT_PEER_DELETE_SUCCEEDED or
0002a7a8  // PM_EVT_PEER_DELETE_FAILED
0002a7a8  08b5       push    {r3, lr}
0002a7aa  044b       ldr     r3, [pc, #0x10]
0002a7ac  1b78       ldrb    r3, [r3]
0002a7ae  13b1       cbz     r3, #0x2a7b6

0002a7b0  fff73ffe   bl      #0x2a432

0002a7b4  08bd       pop     {r3, pc}

0002a7b6  4ff6ff70   movw    r0, #0xffff
0002a7ba  fbe7       b       #0x2a7b4

0002a7bc  void* data_2a7bc = data_20003cea

0002aab8    int32_t pm_peer_rank_highest_update()

0002aab8  // Update peer to highest rank in bonding list
0002aab8  // SDK: components/ble/peer_manager/peer_manager.c
0002aab8  // 
0002aab8  // Promotes peer to top of ranking list (most recently used).
0002aab8  // Used to implement LRU (Least Recently Used) peer database.
0002aab8  // 
0002aab8  // Ranking system:
0002aab8  // - Rank 0: Highest priority (most recent connection)
0002aab8  // - Rank N: Lowest priority (least recent connection)
0002aab8  // - Max peers: Typically 8 on nRF52832 (limited by flash space)
0002aab8  // 
0002aab8  // Rank updates triggered by:
0002aab8  // - BLE_GAP_EVT_CONNECTED: Promote connected peer to rank 0
0002aab8  // - Successful bonding: New peer gets rank 0
0002aab8  // - Re-connection: Existing peer promoted to rank 0
0002aab8  // 
0002aab8  // Update process:
0002aab8  // 1. Read current peer rank from FDS (PM_PEER_DATA_ID_PEER_RANK)
0002aab8  // 2. If already rank 0, no action needed
0002aab8  // 3. Otherwise, increment ranks of all higher-ranked peers
0002aab8  // 4. Set this peer's rank to 0
0002aab8  // 5. Write updated ranks to FDS
0002aab8  // 
0002aab8  // When storage full:
0002aab8  // - pm_peer_delete_lowest_rank() removes lowest-ranked peer
0002aab8  // - Makes space for new bonding
0002aab8  // 
0002aab8  // Parameters:
0002aab8  // - arg1: pm_peer_id_t peer ID to promote
0002aab8  // 
0002aab8  // Peer ranking stored at: data_20003d40 (peer_rank_table)
0002aab8  08b5       push    {r3, lr}
0002aaba  fff72fff   bl      #0x2a91c
0002aabe  08bd       pop     {r3, pc}

0002abf8    void buffer_pool_alloc(int32_t* arg1, int32_t arg2)

0002abf8  // Application: Allocates buffer from pool, checks pool valid
0002abf8  // (arg1!=0, *arg1!=0, arg1[1]!=0), validates arg2 != 0xff, checks if
0002abf8  // already allocated with sub_2ad90, returns buffer pointer (pool[0] +
0002abf8  // pool[3] * index)
0002abf8  38b5       push    {r3, r4, r5, lr}

0002abfc  68b1       cbz     r0, #0x2ac1a

0002ac10  20b1       cbz     r0, #0x2ac1c

0002ac1e  fce7       b       #0x2ac1a


0002ac20    void buffer_pool_free(int32_t* arg1, int32_t arg2)

0002ac20  // Application: Frees buffer from pool, checks pool valid (arg1!=0,
0002ac20  // *arg1!=0, arg1[1]!=0), validates arg2 != 0xff, checks if allocated
0002ac20  // with sub_2ad90, clears bit with sub_2ad22
0002ac20  98b1       cbz     r0, #0x2ac4a

0002ac22  38b5       push    {r3, r4, r5, lr}
0002ac24  0546       mov     r5, r0
0002ac26  0368       ldr     r3, [r0]

0002adb2    int32_t sd_ble_gap_conn_param_update()

0002adb2  7fdf       svc     #0x7f
0002adb4  7047       bx      lr


0002adb6    int32_t sd_ble_gap_authenticate()

0002adb6  // Initiate BLE authentication (pairing/bonding)
0002adb6  // SDK: components/softdevice/s132/headers/ble_gap.h
0002adb6  // 
0002adb6  // Starts pairing/bonding procedure with connected peer.
0002adb6  // 
0002adb6  // SVC call: Supervisor Call to SoftDevice (SVC number 0x7C)
0002adb6  // Parameters:
0002adb6  // - conn_handle: Connection handle to authenticate
0002adb6  // - sec_params: Security parameters structure
0002adb6  // 
0002adb6  // Security parameters (ble_gap_sec_params_t):
0002adb6  // - bond: 1 to save keys (bonding), 0 for pairing only
0002adb6  // - mitm: 1 for Man-In-The-Middle protection (passkey required)
0002adb6  // - lesc: 1 for LE Secure Connections (P-256 ECDH)
0002adb6  // - keypress: 1 to enable keypress notifications
0002adb6  // - io_caps: I/O capabilities (display, keyboard, none)
0002adb6  // - oob: 1 if Out-Of-Band data available
0002adb6  // - min_key_size: 7-16 bytes (encryption key length)
0002adb6  // - max_key_size: 7-16 bytes
0002adb6  // - kdist_own: Key distribution (IRK, CSRK, LTK/EDIV/RAND)
0002adb6  // - kdist_peer: Peer key distribution
0002adb6  // 
0002adb6  // I/O capabilities (determines pairing method):
0002adb6  // - BLE_GAP_IO_CAPS_DISPLAY_ONLY: Display passkey
0002adb6  // - BLE_GAP_IO_CAPS_DISPLAY_YESNO: Display + confirm
0002adb6  // - BLE_GAP_IO_CAPS_KEYBOARD_ONLY: Enter passkey
0002adb6  // - BLE_GAP_IO_CAPS_NONE: Just Works (no MITM)
0002adb6  // - BLE_GAP_IO_CAPS_KEYBOARD_DISPLAY: Display + enter
0002adb6  // 
0002adb6  // Authentication sequence:
0002adb6  // 1. Call sd_ble_gap_authenticate()
0002adb6  // 2. BLE_GAP_EVT_SEC_PARAMS_REQUEST (peer security params)
0002adb6  // 3. BLE_GAP_EVT_PASSKEY_DISPLAY or BLE_GAP_EVT_AUTH_KEY_REQUEST
0002adb6  // 4. BLE_GAP_EVT_AUTH_STATUS (success/failure)
0002adb6  // 5. On success: Keys distributed, peer manager stores to FDS
0002adb6  // 
0002adb6  // Returns: 0 on success, NRF_ERROR_INVALID_STATE if already
0002adb6  // authenticating
0002adb6  86df       svc     #0x86
0002adb8  7047       bx      lr


0002adba    int32_t ble_gap_disconnect_conditional(int32_t arg1, int32_t arg2)

0002adba  // Application: Conditionally disconnects BLE connection, returns 0 if

0002b3ec    int32_t gattc_connection_update(uint32_t arg1, char* arg2, int32_t arg3)

0002b3ec  // Categorizes event handler, checks if discovery needed based on arg2
0002b3ec  // flags.
0002b3ec  // Allocates GATT context, retrieves UUID handles, processes all app
0002b3ec  // contexts.
0002b3ec  // Calls gattc_descriptor_discover if needed for service discovery.
0002b3ec  // Updates BLE connection parameters via sd_ble_gap_conn_param_update.
0002b3ec  // Performs cleanup via gattc_conn_cleanup on completion.
0002b3ec  // Returns 0x3002 if invalid category, else SoftDevice API result.

0002b55e    void gattc_event_dispatcher(int16_t* arg1)

0002b55e  // Application: Dispatches GATT client events by opcode, switch on
0002b55e  // *arg1-0x11: case 0 (0x11=BLE_GATTC_EVT_PRIM_SRVC_DISC_RSP) calls
0002b55e  // gattc_evt_error_handler, case 2 (0x13=BLE_GATTC_EVT_CHAR_DISC_RSP)
0002b55e  // calls gattc_evt_category_handler, case 3
0002b55e  // (0x14=BLE_GATTC_EVT_DESC_DISC_RSP) calls
0002b55e  // gattc_authentication_handler, case 8 (0x19=BLE_GATTC_EVT_WRITE_RSP)
0002b55e  // calls gattc_event_route_by_status, case 9 (0x1a=BLE_GATTC_EVT_HVX)
0002b55e  // calls gattc_reconnect_handler
0002b55e  08b5       push    {r3, lr}
0002b560  0388       ldrh    r3, [r0]
0002b562  113b       subs    r3, #0x11
0002b564  092b       cmp     r3, #9
0002b566  09d8       bhi     #0x2b57c

0002b568  dfe803f0   tbb     [pc, r3]

0002b56c  uint8_t jump_table_2b56c[0xa] = 
0002b56c  {
0002b56c      [0x0] = 0x5
0002b56d      [0x1] = 0x8
0002b56e      [0x2] = 0x9
0002b56f      [0x3] = 0xd
0002b570      [0x4] = 0x8
0002b571      [0x5] = 0x8
0002b572      [0x6] = 0x8
0002b573      [0x7] = 0x8
0002b574      [0x8] = 0x11
0002b575      [0x9] = 0x15
0002b576  }

{Case 0x0}
0002b576  0430       adds    r0, #4
0002b578  fff7acfd   bl      #0x2b0d4

{Case 0x1, 0x4-0x7}
0002b57c  08bd       pop     {r3, pc}

{Case 0x2}
0002b57e  0430       adds    r0, #4
0002b580  fff7defc   bl      #0x2af40
0002b584  fae7       b       #0x2b57c

{Case 0x3}
0002b586  0430       adds    r0, #4
0002b588  fff7bbfd   bl      #0x2b102
0002b58c  f6e7       b       #0x2b57c

{Case 0x8}
0002b58e  0430       adds    r0, #4
0002b590  fff7a8fe   bl      #0x2b2e4
0002b594  f2e7       b       #0x2b57c

{Case 0x9}

0002b598  fff7aefe   bl      #0x2b2f8
0002b59c  eee7       b       #0x2b57c

0002bb68    int32_t app_sched_init()

0002bb68  // Initialize app_scheduler module
0002bb68  // SDK: components/libraries/scheduler/app_scheduler.c
0002bb68  // 
0002bb68  // Initializes the event scheduler for deferred event processing.
0002bb68  // 
0002bb68  // Parameters:
0002bb68  // - event_size: Maximum size of event data (typically 32-64 bytes)
0002bb68  // - queue_size: Maximum number of queued events (typically 10-20)
0002bb68  // - event_buffer: Pointer to buffer for event queue
0002bb68  // 
0002bb68  // Scheduler design:
0002bb68  // - Circular queue (FIFO) for events
0002bb68  // - Each event: [handler_func_ptr, data_size, event_data]
0002bb68  // - Queue stored at: data_20003e00 (event_buffer parameter)
0002bb68  // 
0002bb68  // Queue structure:
0002bb68  // - Head pointer: Next event to dequeue
0002bb68  // - Tail pointer: Next free slot for enqueue
0002bb68  // - Full when: (tail + 1) % queue_size == head
0002bb68  // - Empty when: tail == head
0002bb68  // 
0002bb68  // Event flow:
0002bb68  // 1. Event source calls app_sched_event_put(handler, data, size)
0002bb68  // 2. Event copied to queue[tail], tail++
0002bb68  // 3. Main loop calls app_scheduler_execute()
0002bb68  // 4. Dequeue event from queue[head], head++
0002bb68  // 5. Call handler(p_event_data, event_size)
0002bb68  // 
0002bb68  // Common event sources:
0002bb68  // - app_timer_timeout_handler (defer to main context)
0002bb68  // - Button handlers (process outside interrupt)
0002bb68  // - BLE events (process in main loop)
0002bb68  // - Sensor readings (ADC/COMP results)
0002bb68  // 
0002bb68  // Benefits:
0002bb68  // - Moves processing out of interrupt context
0002bb68  // - Prevents stack overflow in nested interrupts
0002bb68  // - Allows blocking operations in handlers
0002bb68  // - Serializes event processing
0002bb68  // 
0002bb68  // Returns: void (no error checking in SDK implementation)
0002bb68  10b5       push    {r4, lr}
0002bb6a  0024       movs    r4, #0
0002bb6c  054b       ldr     r3, [pc, #0x14]
0002bb6e  1c70       strb    r4, [r3]
0002bb70  054b       ldr     r3, [pc, #0x14]
0002bb72  1c60       str     r4, [r3]
0002bb74  bff35f8f   dmb     SY
0002bb78  0449       ldr     r1, [pc, #0x10]
0002bb7a  0548       ldr     r0, [pc, #0x14]
0002bb7c  f9f7c0fe   bl      #0x25900
0002bb80  2046       mov     r0, r4
0002bb82  10bd       pop     {r4, pc}

0002bb84  int32_t data_2bb84 = 0x20003d55
0002bb88  int32_t data_2bb88 = 0x20003d58
0002bb8c  void* data_2bb8c = data_3a0b4
0002bb90  int32_t data_2bb90 = 0x20003d4c

0002bb94    void app_sched_event_put(int32_t arg1)

0002bb94  // SDK: components/libraries/scheduler/app_scheduler.c - Puts event in
0002bb94  // application scheduler queue, uses STREX atomic operation on
0002bb94  // data_20003d58 for lock, checks data_20003d55 pending flag, sets
0002bb94  // data_20003d54=arg1 (event type), sets data_20003d55=1 (pending),
0002bb94  // calls app_sched_execute if arg1==4, DMB barriers for
0002bb94  // synchronization, clears data_20003d58 lock
0002bb94  08b5       push    {r3, lr}
0002bb96  124b       ldr     r3, [pc, #0x48]
0002bb98  0122       movs    r2, #1

0002bb9a  53e8001f   ldrex   r1, [r3]
0002bb9e  9446       mov     r12, r2
0002bba0  43e800ce   strex   lr, r12, [r3]
0002bba4  9ef0000f   teq     lr, #0
0002bba8  f7d1       bne     #0x2bb9a

0002bbaa  bff35f8f   dmb     SY
0002bbae  81b9       cbnz    r1, #0x2bbd2

0002bbb0  0428       cmp     r0, #4
0002bbb2  07d0       beq     #0x2bbc4

0002bbb4  0b4b       ldr     r3, [pc, #0x2c]
0002bbb6  1b78       ldrb    r3, [r3]
0002bbb8  63b9       cbnz    r3, #0x2bbd4

0002bbba  0b4b       ldr     r3, [pc, #0x2c]
0002bbbc  1870       strb    r0, [r3]
0002bbbe  094b       ldr     r3, [pc, #0x24]
0002bbc0  0122       movs    r2, #1
0002bbc2  1a70       strb    r2, [r3]

0002bbc4  fff798ff   bl      #0x2baf8
0002bbc8  bff35f8f   dmb     SY
0002bbcc  044b       ldr     r3, [pc, #0x10]
0002bbce  0022       movs    r2, #0
0002bbd0  1a60       str     r2, [r3]

0002bbd2  08bd       pop     {r3, pc}

0002bbd4  bff35f8f   dmb     SY
0002bbd8  014b       ldr     r3, [pc, #4]
0002bbda  0022       movs    r2, #0
0002bbdc  1a60       str     r2, [r3]
0002bbde  f8e7       b       #0x2bbd2

0002bbe0  void* data_2bbe0 = data_20003d58

0002bd0e  // *arg1: 0x50 (BLE_GATTC_EVT_HVX) calls gatt_service_hvx_handler,

0002be8c    void adv_service_evt_handler(int32_t arg1)

0002be8c  // Application: Handles advertising service events, checks if
0002be8c  // data_20003d98!=0 && data_20003d9c!=0, calls callback
0002be8c  // data_20003d9c(arg1, 0x20003da0), ignores 0x11 errors, on other
0002be8c  // errors clears *(data_20003d94+0x1a), calls
0002be8c  // gatt_service_characteristic_discover, invokes error callback
0002be8c  // *(data_20003d94+0x14)(3)
0002be8c  08b5       push    {r3, lr}

0002be92  abb1       cbz     r3, #0x2bec0

0002be94  134b       ldr     r3, [pc, #0x4c]
0002be96  5b68       ldr     r3, [r3, #4]
0002be98  93b1       cbz     r3, #0x2bec0

0002be9a  1349       ldr     r1, [pc, #0x4c]
0002be9c  9847       blx     r3

0002c1dc    int32_t coin_cell_saadc_init()

0002c1dc  // Initialize SAADC for coin cell battery voltage measurement
0002c1dc  // Calls saadc_init() with coin_cell_saadc_evt_handler callback
0002c1dc  // Channel config structure on stack:
0002c1dc  // - var_14: unknown config byte
0002c1dc  // - var_10_1: 0x9000002 (gain, reference, acq_time, mode config)
0002c1dc  // - var_c_1: 0 (burst mode disabled)
0002c1dc  // 
0002c1dc  // If data_20003076 flag set:
0002c1dc  // - Overrides config bytes from data_20003070-72
0002c1dc  // 
0002c1dc  // Calls saadc_channel_init(0, &config) to setup channel 0
0002c1dc  // Calls saadc_buffer_convert(0x20003da6, 1) to start conversion
0002c1dc  // Buffer at 0x20003da6 (1 sample)
0002c1dc  // 
0002c1dc  // Returns result of buffer_convert or channel_init
0002c1dc  // Used for monitoring coin cell battery voltage via ADC
0002c1dc  // Triggers coin_cell_saadc_evt_handler when conversion complete
0002c1dc  00b5       push    {lr}
0002c1de  85b0       sub     sp, #0x14
0002c1e0  1349       ldr     r1, [pc, #0x4c]
0002c1e2  0020       movs    r0, #0

0002c360    void init_comparator()

0002c360  // Initialize COMP (Comparator) for battery monitoring
0002c360  // Config structure at stack:
0002c360  // - var_14: REFSEL = 5 (reference voltage selection)
0002c360  // - var_10: ANADETECT = 0 (analog detect mode)
0002c360  // - var_c: PSEL = 0x704 (pin selection and config)
0002c360  // Callback: coin_cell_state_handler - handles battery voltage events
0002c360  // Calls comp_init() with config structure
0002c360  // On success: comp_start(), sets COMP.HYST=1 (hysteresis enabled)
0002c360  // Enables comparator interrupts type 2 via comp_enable_interrupts(2)
0002c360  // On failure: calls reset_entry_point() to restart system
0002c360  // Used for coin cell battery voltage monitoring
0002c360  // Triggers interrupts when battery voltage crosses thresholds
0002c360  00b5       push    {lr}
0002c362  85b0       sub     sp, #0x14
0002c364  01ab       add     r3, sp, #4
0002c366  0c4a       ldr     r2, [pc, #0x30]
0002c368  07ca       ldm     r2, {r0, r1, r2}
0002c36a  83e80700   stm     r3, {r0, r1, r2}
0002c36e  0b49       ldr     r1, [pc, #0x2c]
0002c370  1846       mov     r0, r3
0002c372  f8f71ffb   bl      #0x249b4
0002c376  58b9       cbnz    r0, #0x2c390

0002c378  f8f78cfb   bl      #0x24a94
0002c37c  084b       ldr     r3, [pc, #0x20]
0002c37e  0122       movs    r2, #1
0002c380  c3f83825   str     r2, [r3, #0x538]
0002c384  0220       movs    r0, #2
0002c386  fff7d7ff   bl      #0x2c338
0002c38a  05b0       add     sp, #0x14
0002c38c  5df804fb   pop     {pc}

0002c390  f8f72cfd   bl      #0x24dec
{ Does not return }

0002c394                                                              f0 e7 00 bf                                              ....

0002c3a0  void* data_2c3a0 = COMP

0002c3a4    int32_t sd_ble_gatts_service_add()

0002c3a4  // Add GATT service to attribute table
0002c3a4  // SDK: components/softdevice/s132/headers/ble_gatts.h
0002c3a4  // 
0002c3a4  // Adds a new GATT service to the local GATT server database.
0002c3a4  // 
0002c3a4  // SVC call: Supervisor Call to SoftDevice (SVC number 0x93)
0002c3a4  // Parameters:
0002c3a4  // - type: Service type (BLE_GATTS_SRVC_TYPE_PRIMARY or SECONDARY)
0002c3a4  // - uuid: Service UUID structure (16-bit or 128-bit)
0002c3a4  // - handle: Output pointer to receive service handle
0002c3a4  // 
0002c3a4  // Service types:
0002c3a4  // - BLE_GATTS_SRVC_TYPE_PRIMARY (0x01): Primary service
0002c3a4  // - BLE_GATTS_SRVC_TYPE_SECONDARY (0x02): Secondary service
0002c3a4  // (referenced by primary)
0002c3a4  // 
0002c3a4  // UUID types:
0002c3a4  // - BLE_UUID_TYPE_BLE (0x01): 16-bit Bluetooth SIG UUID
0002c3a4  // - BLE_UUID_TYPE_VENDOR_BEGIN (0x02+): 128-bit vendor-specific UUID
0002c3a4  // 
0002c3a4  // Service handle allocation:
0002c3a4  // - Handle assigned by SoftDevice (starts at 0x0001)
0002c3a4  // - Sequential allocation (service, then characteristics, then
0002c3a4  // descriptors)
0002c3a4  // - Handle returned via p_handle parameter
0002c3a4  // 
0002c3a4  // Built-in services (added automatically):
0002c3a4  // - GAP Service (0x1800): Device name, appearance, connection params
0002c3a4  // - GATT Service (0x1801): Service changed indication
0002c3a4  // 
0002c3a4  // Custom services (must be added):
0002c3a4  // - DIS (0x180a): Device Information Service
0002c3a4  // - Custom 0x1580: Proprietary service for phone app
0002c3a4  // - Custom 0x1554, 0x2554: Additional proprietary services
0002c3a4  // 
0002c3a4  // Service addition order matters for handle allocation.
0002c3a4  // 
0002c3a4  // Returns: 0 on success, NRF_ERROR_NO_MEM if attribute table full
0002c3a4  a0df       svc     #0xa0
0002c3a6  7047       bx      lr


0002c3a8    int32_t sd_ble_gatts_characteristic_add()

0002c3aa  7047       bx      lr

0002d124    void fatal_error_handler() __noreturn

0002d124  // Handle fatal application errors
0002d124  // SDK: Application-specific error handler
0002d124  // 
0002d124  // Handles unrecoverable errors by logging and resetting system.
0002d124  // 
0002d124  // Error sources:
0002d124  // - APP_ERROR_CHECK() macro failures
0002d124  // - SoftDevice assertions (SD_EVT_IRQHandler errors)
0002d124  // - app_error_fault_handler() invocations
0002d124  // - Stack overflow detection
0002d124  // - Memory allocation failures
0002d124  // 
0002d124  // Error information structure (error_info_t):
0002d124  // - line_num: Source line number where error occurred
0002d124  // - p_file_name: Source file name string
0002d124  // - err_code: Error code (NRF_ERROR_* values)
0002d124  // 
0002d124  // Common error codes:
0002d124  // - NRF_ERROR_NO_MEM (0x04): Memory allocation failed
0002d124  // - NRF_ERROR_INVALID_PARAM (0x07): Invalid parameter
0002d124  // - NRF_ERROR_INVALID_STATE (0x08): Invalid state for operation
0002d124  // - NRF_ERROR_BUSY (0x0a): Resource busy
0002d124  // - NRF_ERROR_TIMEOUT (0x0b): Operation timed out
0002d124  // 
0002d124  // Fatal error handling:
0002d124  // 1. Disable all interrupts (__disable_irq())
0002d124  // 2. Log error info to retention RAM (survives reset)
0002d124  // 3. Optionally flash LEDs or update LCD
0002d124  // 4. Call NVIC_SystemReset() to reset device
0002d124  // 5. Bootloader can read error from retention RAM
0002d124  // 
0002d124  // Error persistence:
0002d124  // - Error info stored at: data_20004700 (retention RAM)
0002d124  // - Survives reset if retention RAM powered
0002d124  // - Bootloader/debugger can read on reboot
0002d124  // 
0002d124  // IMPORTANT: This function never returns!
0002d124  // 
0002d124  // Parameters:
0002d124  // - error_info: Pointer to error information structure
0002d124  08b5       push    {r3, lr}
0002d126  f7f761fe   bl      #0x24dec
{ Does not return }

0002d12a                                08 bd                                                                        ..

0002d430    uint32_t pm_peer_count()

0002d430  // Get number of bonded peers in database
0002d430  // SDK: components/ble/peer_manager/peer_manager.c
0002d430  // 
0002d430  // Returns count of currently bonded peers in persistent storage.
0002d430  // 
0002d430  // Count determination:
0002d430  // 1. Iterate through peer ID table at data_20003d00
0002d430  // 2. Check each peer ID for valid bonding data
0002d430  // 3. Verify peer has PM_PEER_DATA_ID_BONDING record in FDS
0002d430  // 4. Count only peers with complete bonding information
0002d430  // 
0002d430  // Typical values:
0002d430  // - 0: No bonded peers (fresh device or after factory reset)
0002d430  // - 1-8: Normal operation (most devices bond with 1-2 peers)
0002d430  // - 8: Database full on nRF52832 (storage limit reached)
0002d430  // 
0002d430  // Use cases:
0002d430  // - Check if database full before accepting new bonding
0002d430  // - Display bonded device count in UI/diagnostics
0002d430  // - Determine if cleanup needed (trigger pm_peer_delete_lowest_rank)
0002d430  // - Factory reset validation (should return 0 after reset)
0002d430  // 
0002d430  // Parameters:
0002d430  // - None
0002d430  // 
0002d430  // Returns: uint32_t count of bonded peers (0-8 typical range)
0002d430  // 
0002d430  // Related: pm_peer_delete_lowest_rank() when count reaches maximum
0002d430  10b5       push    {r4, lr}
0002d432  4ff6ff70   movw    r0, #0xffff
0002d436  fdf7b7f9   bl      #0x2a7a8
0002d43a  0024       movs    r4, #0
0002d43c  03e0       b       #0x2d446

0002d43e  0134       adds    r4, #1
0002d440  e4b2       uxtb    r4, r4
0002d442  fdf7b1f9   bl      #0x2a7a8

0002d446  4ff6ff73   movw    r3, #0xffff
0002d44a  9842       cmp     r0, r3
0002d44c  f7d1       bne     #0x2d43e

0002d44e  2046       mov     r0, r4
0002d450  10bd       pop     {r4, pc}

0002d490    int32_t state_machine_update()

0002d490  // Update application state machine based on current state
0002d490  // data_20005d6f.
0002d490  // If state 8 or 0xe (navigation modes), transitions to 0xb (view
0002d490  // mode).
0002d490  // Otherwise transitions to state 6 (main data screen).
0002d490  // Returns pointer to data_20005d6f state variable.
0002d490  // Simple state transition logic for UI mode switching.
0002d490  08b5       push    {r3, lr}
0002d492  04f0effe   bl      #0x32274
0002d496  0378       ldrb    r3, [r0]
0002d498  082b       cmp     r3, #8
0002d49a  04d0       beq     #0x2d4a6

0002d4bc    void ble_central_evt_handler(int16_t* arg1)

0002d4bc  // Handle BLE central role events (GAP and GATT events).
0002d4bc  // Processes event types 0x00-0x57:
0002d4bc  // - 0x01: Connection established, update parameters
0002d4bc  // - 0x10: Store connection handle in data_200030b0
0002d4bc  // - 0x11: Disconnection, clear handle (0xffff), update state machine
0002d4bc  // - 0x21: GATT attribute info discovery
0002d4bc  // - 0x3b: Timeout event, stop advertising and reset
0002d4bc  // - 0x51: Service changed indication (handles 0x182), requires
0002d4bc  // reconnection
0002d4bc  // - 0x56: Stop advertising on specific event
0002d4bc  // - 0x57: Check/clear data_20004237 flag, call
0002d4bc  // conditional_flag_setter
0002d4bc  // Large switch statement handling BLE stack events.
0002d4bc  // Calls reset_entry_point() on critical errors for system recovery.
0002d4bc  0388       ldrh    r3, [r0]
0002d4be  572b       cmp     r3, #0x57
0002d4c0  00f2c780   bhi     #0x2d652

0002d814    int32_t pm_peer_delete_lowest_rank(int32_t arg1, int32_t arg2)

0002d814  // Delete lowest-ranked peer from database
0002d814  // SDK: components/ble/peer_manager/peer_manager.c
0002d814  // 
0002d814  // Removes least recently used peer when storage is full.
0002d814  // Part of LRU (Least Recently Used) peer management strategy.
0002d814  // 
0002d814  // Deletion triggers:
0002d814  // - PM_EVT_STORAGE_FULL event received
0002d814  // - New bonding attempt when database at capacity
0002d814  // - Automatic cleanup during bonding process
0002d814  // 
0002d814  // Selection algorithm:
0002d814  // 1. Scan all peers in database (iterate file_id in FDS)
0002d814  // 2. Read PM_PEER_DATA_ID_PEER_RANK for each peer
0002d814  // 3. Find peer with highest rank value (least recent)
0002d814  // 4. Call pm_peer_delete() on selected peer
0002d814  // 5. Wait for PM_EVT_PEER_DELETE_SUCCEEDED
0002d814  // 6. Retry bonding operation
0002d814  // 
0002d814  // Peer capacity:
0002d814  // - nRF52832: Typically 8 bonded peers (4KB FDS space)
0002d814  // - Each peer: ~512 bytes (keys + attributes + metadata)
0002d814  // - With GC overhead: 6-8 practical limit
0002d814  // 
0002d814  // Parameters:
0002d814  // - None (automatically selects lowest-ranked peer)
0002d814  // 
0002d814  // Returns: 0 on success, error if database empty
0002d814  // Calls: pm_peer_delete() for selected peer_id
0002d814  // Dispatches: PM_EVT_PEER_DELETE_SUCCEEDED when complete
0002d814  70b5       push    {r4, r5, r6, lr}
0002d816  84b0       sub     sp, #0x10
0002d818  0546       mov     r5, r0
0002d81a  0e46       mov     r6, r1
0002d81c  fff708fe   bl      #0x2d430
0002d820  10f0ff00   ands    r0, r0, #0xff
0002d824  16d1       bne     #0x2d854

0002d826  01ab       add     r3, sp, #4
0002d828  03aa       add     r2, sp, #0xc
0002d82a  02a9       add     r1, sp, #8
0002d82c  0df10e00   add     r0, sp, #0xe
0002d830  fdf710f8   bl      #0x2a854
0002d834  0446       mov     r4, r0
0002d836  86b1       cbz     r6, #0x2d85a

0002d838  bdf80c00   ldrh    r0, [sp, #0xc]
0002d83c  a842       cmp     r0, r5
0002d83e  03d0       beq     #0x2d848

0002d840  4ff6ff73   movw    r3, #0xffff
0002d844  9842       cmp     r0, r3
0002d846  0cd1       bne     #0x2d862

0002d848  0c48       ldr     r0, [pc, #0x30]
0002d84a  01f0e7fe   bl      #0x2f61c

0002d84e  2046       mov     r0, r4
0002d850  04b0       add     sp, #0x10
0002d852  70bd       pop     {r4, r5, r6, pc}

0002da78    void peer_manager_init(bool erase_bonds)

0002da78  // Initialize Peer Manager (BLE bonding/pairing)
0002da78  // Returns early if already initialized (data_20004088==1)
0002da78  // Calls peer_manager_init() to setup peer database
0002da78  // If erase_bonds arg set: calls pm_peers_delete_all() to clear
0002da78  // bonding data
0002da78  // Configures security params:
0002da78  // - Bit 0: bonding enabled
0002da78  // - Bits 1-2: security level cleared (no MITM/LESC)
0002da78  // - Bits 4-5: 0x30 (security mode/level config)
0002da78  // - Bit 7: clear (misc flag)
0002da78  // I/O capabilities: 7 (no input/output)
0002da78  // Min key size: 0x10 (16 bytes)
0002da78  // Max key size: varies by mode
0002da78  // Calls pm_peer_id_get() to retrieve peer ID
0002da78  // Registers callbacks: pm_evt_handler, fds_write_complete_handler
0002da78  // Sets initialized flag data_20004088=1
0002da78  // On any failure: calls reset_entry_point() to restart
0002da78  // SDK: components/ble/peer_manager/peer_manager.c

0002dba8    void format_device_id(char* p_str)

0002dba8  // Format device ID as hex string for BLE advertising
0002dba8  // Reads 8-byte unique device ID from FICR (Factory Information)
0002dba8  // Formats as 16-character hex string "0123456789ABCDEF"
0002dba8  // Output buffer at arg1 must be at least 17 bytes (16 chars + null)
0002dba8  // Uses sprintf to format each byte as 2 hex digits
0002dba8  // Device ID is read from get_device_id() at FICR.DEVICEID registers
0002dba8  // Used in BLE Device Information Service (DIS) serial number
0002dba8  // Provides unique identifier for each nRF52832 chip
0002dba8  08b5       push    {r3, lr}
0002dbaa  4ff08053   mov     r3, #0x10000000
0002dbae  5a6e       ldr     r2, [r3, #0x64]
0002dbb0  1b6e       ldr     r3, [r3, #0x60]
0002dbb2  0249       ldr     r1, [pc, #8]
0002dbb4  0bf0e6fc   bl      #0x39584
0002dbb8  08bd       pop     {r3, pc}

0002dbba                                                                                00 bf                                        ..

0002dbbc  char const (* data_2dbbc)[0x9] = data_3a2bc {"%08x%08x"}

0002dbc0    uint32_t services_init(void* p_context)

0002dbc0  // Initialize all BLE GATT services
0002dbc0  // 1. Device Information Service (DIS):
0002dbc0  //    - Manufacturer: "COMODULE"
0002dbc0  //    - Model: "v3.0.0" formatted string
0002dbc0  //    - Serial: Device ID (formatted via format_device_id)
0002dbc0  // 2. Custom Service 0x1580 (at 0x20004164):
0002dbc0  //    - Protocol command handler at prop_protocol_cmd_handler
0002dbc0  //    - Lookup table at 0x2000407c, handler at lookup_table_search
0002dbc0  // 3. Custom Proprietary Service 1 (at 0x20004188):
0002dbc0  //    - Write handler at ble_prop2_char1_write_handler
0002dbc0  //    - Context at 0x2000307c, buffer at 0x20003f8c
0002dbc0  // 4. Custom Proprietary Service 2 (at 0x200041e0):
0002dbc0  //    - Authentication handler at ble_device_authentication_handler
0002dbc0  //    - Context at 0x20003ea0, buffer at 0x20003078
0002dbc0  // On any failure: calls reset_entry_point() to restart system
0002dbc0  // Returns 0 on success
0002dbc0  // Critical service setup for phone app communication

0002e43c    void gpio_init()

0002e43c  // Initialize GPIO pins for peripherals
0002e43c  // Loops through pins 2-31, configures based on function:
0002e43c  // - Pins 29-30, 31, 24, 23: Set to disconnected (mode 0)
0002e43c  // - Pin 12: Set to disconnected
0002e43c  // - Pin 22: Set to disconnected  
0002e43c  // - Pin 15: Output with pullup (mode 3), set high (P0.OUTSET=0x8000)
0002e43c  // - Pin 16: Set to disconnected
0002e43c  // - Pin 3: Set to disconnected
0002e43c  // - Pin 21 (0x15): Skipped (used elsewhere)
0002e43c  // - Default: Disconnected (mode 4)
0002e43c  // Critical for ensuring unused pins don't float and waste power
0002e43c  // Sets up initial pin states before peripheral initialization

0002e4ea    void main_app()

0002e4ea  // Main application loop - never returns
0002e4ea  // Initialization sequence:
0002e4ea  // 1. gpio_init() - configure all GPIO pins
0002e4ea  // 2. wdt_init(0x12c) - watchdog timer (300ms timeout)
0002e4ea  // 3. power_management_init() - setup power modes
0002e4ea  // 4. log_init() - initialize logging system
0002e4ea  // 5. ble_stack_init() - start BLE stack and clocks
0002e4ea  // 
0002e4ea  // Main loop (infinite):
0002e4ea  // - app_state_machine() - run main state machine
0002e4ea  // - idle_state_handle() - process idle tasks
0002e4ea  // - If idle returns non-zero: sd_app_evt_wait() - wait for SoftDevice
0002e4ea  // events
0002e4ea  // - power_manage(0) - enter low power mode
0002e4ea  // 
0002e4ea  // This is the main application entry point that runs continuously
0002e4ea  // Never returns - runs until reset or power off
0002e4ea  08b5       push    {r3, lr}
0002e4ec  fff7a6ff   bl      #0x2e43c
0002e4f0  4ff49670   mov     r0, #0x12c

0002e540    uint32_t periodic_data_sender()

0002e540  // Checks communication ready flag and mode state.
0002e540  // Increments counter data_200043fc when timestamp changes.

0002e540  // (8 bytes).

0002e540  // bytes).
0002e540  // Sets flags (data_20008554, data_20008450) after successful
0002e540  // serialization.

0002e614    uint32_t app_timer_handler()

0002e614  // Main application timer handler called every 25ms (0x19 ticks).
0002e614  // Increments data_200044e0 timestamp, wraps at 86400000 (24 hours).
0002e614  // Periodic tasks based on modulo checks:
0002e614  // - Every cycle (25ms): data_poll_and_pack(), periodic_data_sender()
0002e614  // - Every 50ms (mod 0x32): vehicle state handler, button processing
0002e614  // - Every 100ms (mod 0x64): set_flag_20005e76()
0002e614  // - Every 1000ms (mod 0x3e8): svc_1580_notify_with_counter(), comm
0002e614  // handler
0002e614  // Initial run (data_20005090==0): sends CAN filter config.
0002e614  // Central timing hub for all periodic application tasks.

0002ea94    void rtc_125ms_tick_handler(ret_code_t arg1)

0002ea94  // Handle 125ms RTC tick for timekeeping
0002ea94  // SDK: Application-specific
0002ea94  // 
0002ea94  // Processes 125ms tick events from RTC2 for time tracking.
0002ea94  // 
0002ea94  // Time tracking:
0002ea94  // - Tick counter at data_20004604: Increments every call (125ms)
0002ea94  // - Unix time at data_20004600: Increments every 8 ticks (1 second)
0002ea94  // - Calculation: if (tick_counter % 8 == 0) unix_time++
0002ea94  // 
0002ea94  // Unix time synchronization:
0002ea94  // - Initial value: Set from phone app via BLE
0002ea94  // - CAN message 0x101: Receives Unix timestamp from motor controller
0002ea94  // - Format: 32-bit seconds since epoch (Jan 1, 1970)
0002ea94  // - Timezone: UTC (app handles local timezone conversion)
0002ea94  // 
0002ea94  // Time-dependent operations:
0002ea94  // - LCD refresh: Check if time display needs update
0002ea94  // - Session timeout: Calculate time since last activity
0002ea94  // - Logging: Timestamp for diagnostic events
0002ea94  // - CAN messages: Some include timestamp for synchronization
0002ea94  // 
0002ea94  // Tick rollover handling:
0002ea94  // - Tick counter: 32-bit, rolls over after 497 days
0002ea94  // - Unix time: 32-bit, Y2038 problem (rolls over Feb 2038)
0002ea94  // 
0002ea94  // Called from: RTC2_IRQHandler every 125ms
0002ea94  // Parameters: None (operates on global state)
0002ea94  0428       cmp     r0, #4
0002ea96  00d0       beq     #0x2ea9a

0002ed4c    int32_t rtc_get_unix_time()

0002ed4c  // Get current Unix timestamp
0002ed4c  // SDK: Application-specific
0002ed4c  // 
0002ed4c  // Returns current Unix time in seconds since epoch.
0002ed4c  // 
0002ed4c  // Time source:
0002ed4c  // - Unix time stored at: data_20004600
0002ed4c  // - Updated by: rtc_125ms_tick_handler every second
0002ed4c  // - Initially set: Via BLE from phone app or CAN 0x101 message
0002ed4c  // 
0002ed4c  // Unix time format:
0002ed4c  // - Type: uint32_t (32-bit unsigned)
0002ed4c  // - Units: Seconds since January 1, 1970 00:00:00 UTC
0002ed4c  // - Range: 0 to 4,294,967,295 (year 2106)
0002ed4c  // - Y2038 problem: Rolls over February 2038
0002ed4c  // 
0002ed4c  // Accuracy:
0002ed4c  // - Source: 32.768 kHz LFCLK crystal (20 ppm typical)
0002ed4c  // - Drift: ~1.7 seconds per day without sync
0002ed4c  // - Sync: Periodic updates from phone app via BLE
0002ed4c  // - Resolution: 1 second (125ms ticks accumulated)
0002ed4c  // 
0002ed4c  // Use cases:
0002ed4c  // - Timestamp for logged events
0002ed4c  // - Calculate session duration
0002ed4c  // - Display time on LCD (requires timezone conversion)
0002ed4c  // - Synchronize with motor controller via CAN
0002ed4c  // - Generate time-based authentication tokens
0002ed4c  // 
0002ed4c  // Parameters:
0002ed4c  // - None
0002ed4c  // 
0002ed4c  // Returns: uint32_t Unix timestamp (seconds since epoch)
0002ed4c  014b       ldr     r3, [pc, #4]
0002ed4e  1868       ldr     r0, [r3]
0002ed50  7047       bx      lr

0002ed52                                                        00 bf                                                        ..

0002ed54  int32_t data_2ed54 = 0x200030b4

0002ed58    void ble_stack_init()

0002ed58  // Initialize BLE stack and peripherals
0002ed58  // Calls clock_lfclk_request_init() - starts low frequency clock for
0002ed58  // timers
0002ed58  // Calls rtc2_ppi_timer_init() - initializes RTC2 with PPI for timer
0002ed58  // system
0002ed58  // Critical early initialization for BLE and timing subsystems
0002ed58  // Must be called before any BLE operations
0002ed58  // SDK: Based on components/softdevice/common/nrf_sdh.c pattern
0002ed58  08b5       push    {r3, lr}
0002ed5a  fff719fe   bl      #0x2e990
0002ed5e  fff72bfe   bl      #0x2e9b8
0002ed62  08bd       pop     {r3, pc}


0002ed64    void power_manage(char arg1)

0002ed64  // Set power management idle flag
0002ed64  // Stores arg1 to data_2000461c (idle flag)
0002ed64  // Used by idle_state_handle() to determine if system can sleep
0002ed64  // Non-zero: system cannot enter low power mode
0002ed64  // Zero: system can call sd_app_evt_wait() for power saving
0002ed64  // Called from main_app() main loop with result of idle checks
0002ed64  // Simple flag setter for power state management
0002ed64  014b       ldr     r3, [pc, #4]
0002ed66  1870       strb    r0, [r3]

0002ed7c    int32_t rtc_init()

0002ed7c  // Initialize RTC2 for real-time clock functionality
0002ed7c  // SDK: Application-specific RTC implementation
0002ed7c  // 
0002ed7c  // Configures RTC2 peripheral for timekeeping and periodic tasks.
0002ed7c  // 
0002ed7c  // RTC2 configuration (base 0x40024000):
0002ed7c  // - PRESCALER: 4095 (32768 Hz / 4096 = 8 Hz base frequency)
0002ed7c  // - CC[0]: Compare channel 0 for periodic interrupts
0002ed7c  // - EVTEN: Enable COMPARE[0] event
0002ed7c  // - INTENSET: Enable COMPARE[0] interrupt
0002ed7c  // - TASKS_START: Start RTC2 counter
0002ed7c  // 
0002ed7c  // Tick period calculation:
0002ed7c  // - RTC clock: 32.768 kHz (LFCLK)
0002ed7c  // - Prescaler: 4095 (divide by 4096)
0002ed7c  // - Base frequency: 32768 / 4096 = 8 Hz (125ms per tick)
0002ed7c  // - CC[0] period: 1 tick = 125ms
0002ed7c  // 
0002ed7c  // Interrupt handler: RTC2_IRQHandler
0002ed7c  // - Calls: rtc_125ms_tick_handler every 125ms
0002ed7c  // - Updates: Unix timestamp at data_20004600
0002ed7c  // - Increments: data_20004604 (tick counter)
0002ed7c  // 
0002ed7c  // Unix time management:
0002ed7c  // - Initial time: Set via BLE from phone app (CAN 0x101 message)
0002ed7c  // - Storage: data_20004600 (uint32_t seconds since epoch)
0002ed7c  // - Update: +1 second every 8 ticks (8 * 125ms = 1000ms)
0002ed7c  // 
0002ed7c  // Parameters:
0002ed7c  // - None
0002ed7c  // 
0002ed7c  // Called from: init_routine() during system initialization

0002eea4    int32_t sha1_hash(int32_t* arg1, int32_t* arg2, int32_t* arg3)

0002eea4  // SHA-1 hash implementation
0002eea4  // arg1: Input block 1 (20 bytes / 5 words)
0002eea4  // arg2: Input block 2 (20 bytes / 5 words)
0002eea4  // arg3: Output hash (20 bytes / 5 words)
0002eea4  // Uses SHA-1 state from data_200045f4-0x20004604 (5 words)
0002eea4  // Standard SHA-1 algorithm implementation:
0002eea4  // - Prepares 80-word message schedule (W[0]-W[79])
0002eea4  // - Pads input with 0x80000000 and length 0x140 (320 bits)
0002eea4  // - Performs 80 rounds with 4 different K constants:
0002eea4  //   * Rounds 0-19: K=0x5a827999, f=(B&C)|((~B)&D)
0002eea4  //   * Rounds 20-39: K=0x6ed9eba1, f=B^C^D
0002eea4  //   * Rounds 40-59: K=0x8f1bbcdc, f=(B&C)|(B&D)|(C&D)
0002eea4  //   * Rounds 60-79: K=0xca62c1d6, f=B^C^D
0002eea4  // - Updates 5-word hash state A-E via rotate_left operations
0002eea4  // Returns 0 on completion
0002eea4  // Used for generating authentication tokens or session IDs
0002eea4  // SDK: Standard cryptographic SHA-1 implementation

0002f3c8    int32_t parse_int_from_string(char* arg1, int32_t* arg2)

0002f3c8  // Parse decimal integer from string with optional negative sign.
0002f3c8  // Reads digits 0-9, stops at first non-digit or comma character.
0002f3c8  // Updates arg2 index pointer as parsing progresses.

0002f41a    int32_t parse_comma_int(char* arg1, int32_t* arg2)

0002f41a  // Parse hexadecimal integer from comma-delimited string.
0002f41a  // Accepts hex digits: 0-9, A-F (uppercase), a-f (lowercase).
0002f41a  // Shifts accumulator left by 4 bits (<<4) for each digit.

0002f940    int32_t can_process_nrf6_message(char* arg1)

0002f940  // Process $NRF,6,* UART message (13 hex bytes) from STM - extended
0002f940  // format.
0002f940  // Parses message type, validates checksum, extracts payload.
0002f940  // Special command handling:
0002f940  // - 0xfe01: Device reset command (validates against data_20005194
0002f940  // key)
0002f940  // - 0xfe02: Enter sleep mode (display state 4)
0002f940  // - 0xfe0d: Send device ID back via 0xfe0a message
0002f940  // - 0xfe10: Display control commands (1-8):
0002f940  //   * 1: Enable features (data_20004e34=1), send FE15
0002f940  //   * 2: Disable features, send FE15
0002f940  //   * 3: Display all pixels on (state 0x1b)
0002f940  //   * 4: Display all pixels off (state 0x1a)
0002f940  //   * 5: Clear display, normal mode
0002f940  //   * 6: Send FE17 message
0002f940  //   * 7: Send FE19 timestamp
0002f940  //   * 8: Send FE18 sensor data
0002f940  // Provides STMnRF remote control interface for testing and
0002f940  // diagnostics.
0002f940  30b5       push    {r4, r5, lr}
0002f942  93b0       sub     sp, #0x4c
0002f944  0546       mov     r5, r0
0002f946  0723       movs    r3, #7
0002f948  1193       str     r3, [sp, #0x44]
0002f94a  0024       movs    r4, #0
0002f94c  0ae0       b       #0x2f964

0002f94e  11a9       add     r1, sp, #0x44

0002fc70    int32_t uart_command_parser(char* arg1)

0002fc70  // Parse and dispatch UART commands from STM
0002fc70  // Recognizes these command prefixes:
0002fc70  // 1. "$NRF,5," (7 bytes) -> can_process_nrf5_message() - 11-byte hex
0002fc70  // CAN message
0002fc70  // 2. "$NRF,6," (7 bytes) -> can_process_nrf6_message() - 13-byte hex
0002fc70  // extended CAN
0002fc70  // 3. "$STM,FW," (8 bytes) -> stm_firmware_update_handler() - STM
0002fc70  // firmware update protocol
0002fc70  // 4. "$NRF,CAN,READY" (14 bytes) -> sets data_20005090=1 (CAN ready
0002fc70  // flag)
0002fc70  // 5. "$NRF,CAN,BAUD" (13 bytes) -> responds with
0002fc70  // "$NRF,CAN,BAUD,KB,fa*" (250kbps)
0002fc70  // 6. "$NRF,CAN,FILTER" (15 bytes) -> can_send_filter_config(),
0002fc70  // uart_send_buffer()
0002fc70  // 
0002fc70  // Returns 0 on success
0002fc70  // Core UART protocol dispatcher for STMnRF communication
0002fc70  // Handles CAN messages, firmware updates, and configuration
0002fc70  10b5       push    {r4, lr}
0002fc72  b8b0       sub     sp, #0xe0
0002fc74  0446       mov     r4, r0
0002fc76  0722       movs    r2, #7
0002fc78  2449       ldr     r1, [pc, #0x90]
0002fc7a  09f0c2fc   bl      #0x39602
0002fc7e  28b9       cbnz    r0, #0x2fc8c

0002fc80  2046       mov     r0, r4
0002fc82  fff707fc   bl      #0x2f494

0002fc86  0020       movs    r0, #0
0002fc88  38b0       add     sp, #0xe0
0002fc8a  10bd       pop     {r4, pc}

0002fc8c  0722       movs    r2, #7
0002fc8e  2049       ldr     r1, [pc, #0x80]
0002fc90  2046       mov     r0, r4
0002fc92  09f0b6fc   bl      #0x39602
0002fc96  18b9       cbnz    r0, #0x2fca0

0002fc98  2046       mov     r0, r4
0002fc9a  fff751fe   bl      #0x2f940
0002fc9e  f2e7       b       #0x2fc86

0002fca0  0822       movs    r2, #8
0002fca2  1c49       ldr     r1, [pc, #0x70]
0002fca4  2046       mov     r0, r4
0002fca6  09f0acfc   bl      #0x39602
0002fcaa  18b9       cbnz    r0, #0x2fcb4

0002fd2c    void uart_init(uint8_t tx_pin, uint8_t rx_pin, uint8_t rts_pin, uint8_t cts_pin, bool flow_control, uint32_t baud_rate)

0002fd2c  // Initialize UART peripheral for STM communication
0002fd2c  // Resets: g_uart_rx_buffer_index=0, g_uart_command_callback=0
0002fd2c  // Disables UART, configures pins:
0002fd2c  // - PSELTXD = rx_pin (note: swapped naming?)
0002fd2c  // - PSELRXD = cts_pin
0002fd2c  // If flow_control enabled:
0002fd2c  // - Configures RTS/CTS pins with pullup/open-drain
0002fd2c  // - PSELCTS = rts_pin, PSELRTS = tx_pin
0002fd2c  // Sets CONFIG register to 0x1 (hardware flow control)
0002fd2c  // Sets BAUDRATE to baud_rate parameter
0002fd2c  // Enables UART (ENABLE=4), starts TX/RX tasks
0002fd2c  // Clears EVENTS_RXDRDY, disables all interrupts, enables RXDRDY
0002fd2c  // interrupt (bit 2)
0002fd2c  // Enables NVIC IRQ 2 with priority 0xe0
0002fd2c  // Used for nRF52832  STM32 communication ($NRF,* protocol)
0002fd2c  70b4       push    {r4, r5, r6}

0002fe50  int32_t data_2fe50 = 0x20005070

0002fe54    void wdt_init(uint32_t timeout_ms)

0002fe54  // Initialize watchdog timer
0002fe54  // SDK: components/drivers_nrf/nrf_drv_wdt/nrf_drv_wdt.c
0002fe54  // 
0002fe54  // Configures and starts the watchdog timer for system recovery.
0002fe54  // 
0002fe54  // WDT registers (base 0x40010000):
0002fe54  // - TASKS_START (0x000): Start watchdog
0002fe54  // - CRV (0x504): Counter reload value (timeout period)
0002fe54  // - RREN (0x508): Reload request enable (channels 0-7)
0002fe54  // - CONFIG (0x50c): Configuration (sleep behavior, halt on debug)
0002fe54  // - RR[0] (0x600): Reload request register (write 0x6e524635 to feed)
0002fe54  // 
0002fe54  // Configuration:
0002fe54  // - Timeout: 300ms (CRV = 300 * 32768 / 1000 = 9830 ticks)
0002fe54  // - Run during sleep: Yes (CONFIG.SLEEP = 1)
0002fe54  // - Halt on debug: Yes (CONFIG.HALT = 1)
0002fe54  // - Reload channels: RR[0] enabled
0002fe54  // 
0002fe54  // Watchdog feeding:
0002fe54  // - Must write 0x6e524635 to WDT->RR[0] before timeout
0002fe54  // - Fed from: Main loop, app_state_machine, critical sections
0002fe54  // - Missing feed = system reset
0002fe54  // 
0002fe54  // Reset reason after WDT reset: RESETREAS.DOG = 1
0002fe54  // 
0002fe54  // Parameters:
0002fe54  // - arg1: uint32_t timeout_ms (typically 300)
0002fe54  // 
0002fe54  // Called from: main_app() early in initialization
0002fe54  064b       ldr     r3, [pc, #0x18]
0002fe56  0121       movs    r1, #1
0002fe58  c3f80c15   str     r1, [r3, #0x50c]
0002fe5c  c003       lsls    r0, r0, #0xf
0002fe5e  c3f80405   str     r0, [r3, #0x504]
0002fe62  d3f80825   ldr     r2, [r3, #0x508]
0002fe66  0a43       orrs    r2, r1
0002fe68  c3f80825   str     r2, [r3, #0x508]
0002fe6c  1960       str     r1, [r3]
0002fe6e  7047       bx      lr

0002fe70  void* data_2fe70 = WDT

0002fe74    int32_t app_scheduler_execute()

0002fe74  // Execute queued scheduler events
0002fe74  // SDK: components/libraries/scheduler/app_scheduler.c
0002fe74  // 
0002fe74  // Processes all pending events from the app_scheduler queue.
0002fe74  // Dequeues events and calls registered handler functions.
0002fe74  // 
0002fe74  // Scheduler operation:
0002fe74  // - Events queued by: app_sched_event_put()
0002fe74  // - Queue stored at: data_20003e00 (circular buffer)
0002fe74  // - Max events: Typically 10-20 (configured at compile time)
0002fe74  // - Event structure: handler function pointer + context data
0002fe74  // 
0002fe74  // Event processing:
0002fe74  // 1. Check if queue empty (head == tail)
0002fe74  // 2. If events pending, dequeue next event
0002fe74  // 3. Call event handler with context data
0002fe74  // 4. Update queue head pointer
0002fe74  // 5. Repeat until queue empty or max iterations reached
0002fe74  // 
0002fe74  // Common event sources:
0002fe74  // - app_timer callbacks (deferred to main context)
0002fe74  // - BLE stack events (processed in main loop)
0002fe74  // - Button handlers (debouncing complete)
0002fe74  // - Sensor readings (ADC/COMP results ready)
0002fe74  // 
0002fe74  // Parameters:
0002fe74  // - None
0002fe74  // 
0002fe74  // Called from: Main loop (app_state_machine)
0002fe74  // Returns: void (processes until queue empty)
0002fe74  // 
0002fe74  // Queue full handling: Returns error from app_sched_event_put()
0002fe74  024b       ldr     r3, [pc, #8]
0002fe76  034a       ldr     r2, [pc, #0xc]
0002fe78  c3f80026   str     r2, [r3, #0x600]
0002fe7c  7047       bx      lr

0002fe7e                                                                                            00 bf                                ..

0002fe80  void* data_2fe80 = WDT

0002fea0    uint32_t serialize_settings_to_string(void* arg1, char* arg2, int32_t arg3)

0002fea0  // Serialize dispatch table settings to semicolon-delimited string.
0002fea0  // Format: "timestamp;value1;value2;...;" based on arg3 flag mask.
0002fea0  // Loops through 25 entries (0x18+1) in dispatch table (arg1+0x38).
0002fea0  // Each entry has:
0002fea0  // - Offset +0xc: flags (bit 0=dirty, cleared after serialization)
0002fea0  // - Offset +6: data type (0-5: int8, int16, int32, uint8, uint16,
0002fea0  // uint32)
0002fea0  // - Offset +8: value to serialize
0002fea0  // Only serializes entries matching arg3 flag mask (bits 1+).
0002fea0  // Includes timestamp prefix via rtc_get_unix_time().
0002fea0  // Stops if output exceeds 240 bytes (0xf0).
0002fea0  // Returns count of serialized values.
0002fea0  // Used for BLE characteristic updates and periodic data sync.
0002fea0  2de9f04f   push    {r4, r5, r6, r7, r8, r9, r10, r11, lr}
0002fea4  83b0       sub     sp, #0xc
0002fea6  0646       mov     r6, r0

0002fff8    int32_t update_setting(int32_t arg1, int32_t arg2)

0002fff8  // Update setting value in dispatch table if changed.
0002fff8  // Table entry: g_dispatch_table_entry_0 + (arg2 * 5 * 4).
0002fff8  // Checks if value at offset +8 equals arg1 (already set).
0002fff8  // Checks if offset +5 flag is set (update blocked).
0002fff8  // Sets new value, sets bit 0 of flags at offset +0xc (dirty flag).
0002fff8  // Returns 1 if updated, 0 if unchanged or blocked.
0002fff8  // Used to track CAN message data changes for transmission.
0002fff8  0d4b       ldr     r3, [pc, #0x34]
0002fffa  9b6b       ldr     r3, [r3, #0x38]
0002fffc  01eb8101   add     r1, r1, r1, lsl #2

00030148    void app_context_init(void* p_context)

00030148  // Initialize application context system
00030148  // SDK: Application-specific
00030148  // 
00030148  // Initializes application-wide context and state management.
00030148  // 
00030148  // Context initialization:
00030148  // 1. Call app_context_table_init() - Initialize context table
00030148  // 2. Call app_context_system_init() - Initialize system context
00030148  // 3. Call app_context_entry_init() - Initialize context entries
00030148  // 4. Zero out context RAM at data_20005000
00030148  // 
00030148  // Application context structure:
00030148  // - Global state variables
00030148  // - Configuration parameters
00030148  // - Runtime statistics
00030148  // - Session data
00030148  // 
00030148  // Context table (data_20005000):
00030148  // - Entry count: Number of active context entries
00030148  // - Entry array: Context entry structures
00030148  // - Each entry: [type, id, size, p_data]
00030148  // 
00030148  // Context types:
00030148  // - SYSTEM_CONTEXT: Core system state
00030148  // - SESSION_CONTEXT: Current session data
00030148  // - VEHICLE_CONTEXT: Vehicle/motor controller state
00030148  // - UI_CONTEXT: Display and button state
00030148  // - COMM_CONTEXT: Communication (BLE, UART, CAN) state
00030148  // 
00030148  // Context entry operations:
00030148  // - app_context_get(): Retrieve context by ID
00030148  // - app_context_set(): Update context by ID
00030148  // - app_context_clear(): Clear context entry
00030148  // - app_context_save(): Persist to FDS
00030148  // 
00030148  // Initialization order matters:
00030148  // 1. app_context_init() - Early in init_routine()
00030148  // 2. Load settings from FDS
00030148  // 3. Apply defaults if no saved settings
00030148  // 4. Update context with loaded values
00030148  // 
00030148  // Context used by:
00030148  // - State machines (app_state_machine)
00030148  // - Settings management
00030148  // - UI display (lcd_draw_*)
00030148  // - CAN message processing
00030148  // 
00030148  // Called from: init_routine() before other module init
00030148  38b5       push    {r3, r4, r5, lr}
0003014a  0446       mov     r4, r0
0003014c  4ff42372   mov     r2, #0x28c
00030150  0021       movs    r1, #0
00030152  f3f7ebf8   bl      #0x2332c

0003026e    int32_t save_settings(int32_t arg1)

0003026e  // Save critical settings to FDS (Flash Data Storage).
0003026e  // Builds two 10-byte records for persistence:
0003026e  // Record 1 (0xfc): arg1 value (3 bytes), data_20005180 (2 bytes),
0003026e  // padding
0003026e  // Record 2 (0xfa/0xfb): Trip odometer (data_200051a0, 4B), total
0003026e  // odometer (data_200051a4, 4B)
0003026e  // Calls insert_into_sorted_list to queue FDS write operations.
0003026e  // Preserves odometer values and system state across power cycles.
0003026e  // Critical for maintaining user data integrity.

00030484    void system_reset_with_mode(char const* const arg1)

00030484  // Perform system reset with different modes:
00030484  // Mode 0: Clear all state, reset to defaults, update settings 0x14
00030484  // and 0x13
00030484  // Mode 1: Normal reset, preserve settings, set g_mode_setting based
00030484  // on data_2000519d
00030484  // Mode 2: Factory reset mode (0xAA marker)
00030484  // Mode 3: DFU/bootloader mode (0xA5 marker)
00030484  // Modes 1-3 start 3000ms (0xbb8) timer before reset.

0003048a  dfe800f0   tbb     [pc, r0]

0003048f      [0x1] = 0x22

00030491      [0x3] = 0x66
00030492  }

000305b0    uint32_t send_motor_control_msg()

000305b0  // Send motor control message (0x300) to STM via UART.
000305b0  // Builds control packet with:
000305b0  // - Mode setting (g_mode_setting: 1=normal, 4=alt mode based on
000305b0  // data_2000519d)

00030818    int32_t vehicle_update_handler()

00030818  // Handle vehicle firmware update completion.
00030818  // Resets communication flags, enters 32K erase sleep mode.
00030818  // Checks update status: data_20005c13==0  failed (state 0x16),
00030818  // else success (0x15).
00030818  // If successful and data_20005c14==1, copies data and sends NRF
00030818  // protocol message.
00030818  // Displays final UI update screen, waits 3000000 cycles.
00030818  // If update failed and data_20005c21!=0xab, triggers system reset.
00030818  // Otherwise returns to main screen (state 6).
00030818  // Critical for OTA firmware update flow completion.

0003081c  5148       ldr     r0, [pc, #0x144]

0003082a  fff703fc   bl      #0x30034
0003082e  80f82650   strb    r5, [r0, #0x26]

00030b74  void* data_30b74 = data_2000576e
00030b78  void* data_30b78 = data_20005c10

00030b7c    void process_can_message(uint16_t can_id, uint8_t* data, uint8_t length)

00030b7c  // Master CAN message dispatcher - processes all motor controller CAN
00030b7c  // messages.
00030b7c  // Massive switch statement handling 30+ CAN IDs (0x100-0x5ff):
00030b7c  // 
00030b7c  // **System Messages (0x100-0x101):**
00030b7c  // - 0x100: STM status (0xa5/0x5a=ready), sets data_20005402 mode,
00030b7c  // comm flags
00030b7c  // - 0x101: RTC timestamp sync from motor controller
00030b7c  // 
00030b7c  // **Vehicle Data (0x200-0x212):**
00030b7c  // - 0x200: Error codes (14-bit bitmask), maps to error display
00030b7c  // - 0x201: Speed data, triggers update complete if in DFU mode
00030b7c  // - 0x202: Battery voltage
00030b7c  // - 0x203: Current/power, averaged over 3 samples
00030b7c  // - 0x210: Odometer, SOC, region code (R/Z/S), calculates
00030b7c  // data_20005c68 
00030b7c  // - 0x211: Additional odometer digits (hex ASCII conversion)
00030b7c  // - 0x212: Market mode detect (US=0x45+0x55, EU=other), sets assist
00030b7c  // tables
00030b7c  // 
00030b7c  // **Motor Status (0x400-0x423):**
00030b7c  // - 0x400: Motor state word at 0x20005c66, error bit 0x80 check
00030b7c  // - 0x401: Extended motor parameters
00030b7c  // - 0x402: Motor status byte, triggers error screens (0x17/0xb)
00030b7c  // - 0x403: Temperature data
00030b7c  // - 0x423: Magic sequence (0x88dd...) triggers sleep mode
00030b7c  // 
00030b7c  // **Firmware Update (0x5aa, 0x5ff):**
00030b7c  // - 0x5aa: DFU progress packets, verification, completion signals
00030b7c  // - 0x5ff: Bootloader commands (0x1f50/0x1f51), error reporting
00030b7c  // 
00030b7c  // **Odometer Update (0x266, 0x466):**
00030b7c  // - 0x266: Trip odometer, saves to FDS if changed
00030b7c  // - 0x466: Total odometer (hex ASCII), saves to FDS
00030b7c  // 
00030b7c  // Handles DFU state machine transitions, market detection, error
00030b7c  // mapping.
00030b7c  // Critical hub for all vehicledisplay communication.
00030b7c  f0b5       push    {r4, r5, r6, r7, lr}
00030b7e  99b0       sub     sp, #0x64
00030b80  0446       mov     r4, r0
00030b82  037a       ldrb    r3, [r0, #8]
00030b84  002b       cmp     r3, #0
00030b86  40f01884   bne     #0x313ba

00030b8a  0388       ldrh    r3, [r0]

00030b90  9342       cmp     r3, r2
00030b92  00f07382   beq     #0x3107c

00030b96  4dd8       bhi     #0x30c34

00030b98  40f21222   movw    r2, #0x212
00030b9c  9342       cmp     r3, r2
00030b9e  00f20884   bhi     #0x313b2

00030ba2  b3f5007f   cmp     r3, #0x200

00031490    uint32_t calculate_checksum(void* arg1, int32_t arg2)

00031490  // Calculate simple 8-bit checksum by summing bytes.
00031490  // Loops through buffer summing all bytes, returns lower 8 bits of
00031490  // sum.
00031490  // Used for data validation in UART protocol, flash operations.
00031490  // Standard checksum algorithm for error detection.
00031490  8446       mov     r12, r0
00031492  0023       movs    r3, #0
00031494  1a46       mov     r2, r3
00031496  04e0       b       #0x314a2

00031498  1cf80300   ldrb    r0, [r12, r3]
0003149c  0244       add     r2, r0
0003149e  92b2       uxth    r2, r2
000314a0  0133       adds    r3, #1

000314a2  8b42       cmp     r3, r1
000314a4  f8db       blt     #0x31498

000314a6  d0b2       uxtb    r0, r2
000314a8  7047       bx      lr

000314ac    uint32_t send_motor_status_msg()

000314ac  // Send motor status message (0x302) to STM via UART.
000314ac  // Builds 20-byte message with:
000314ac  // - Message type: 0x302
000314ac  // - Length: 8 bytes payload
000314ac  // - data_20005c71 (motor state)
000314ac  // - CAN message 0x1ac data (motor parameters)
000314ac  // Calls send_nrf_protocol_message to format and transmit.
000314ac  // Part of periodic motor monitoring communication.
000314ac  10b5       push    {r4, lr}
000314ae  88b0       sub     sp, #0x20
000314b0  03ac       add     r4, sp, #0xc
000314b2  1422       movs    r2, #0x14
000314b4  0021       movs    r1, #0
000314b6  2046       mov     r0, r4
000314b8  f1f738ff   bl      #0x2332c
000314bc  40f20233   movw    r3, #0x302
000314c0  adf80c30   strh    r3, [sp, #0xc]
000314c4  0823       movs    r3, #8
000314c6  8df81630   strb    r3, [sp, #0x16]
000314ca  134b       ldr     r3, [pc, #0x4c]
000314cc  93f86130   ldrb    r3, [r3, #0x61]
000314d0  8df81730   strb    r3, [sp, #0x17]
000314d4  fef7aefd   bl      #0x30034
000314d8  836b       ldr     r3, [r0, #0x38]
000314da  d3f8ac31   ldr     r3, [r3, #0x1ac]
000314de  1b0a       lsrs    r3, r3, #8
000314e0  8df81830   strb    r3, [sp, #0x18]
000314e4  fef7a6fd   bl      #0x30034
000314e8  836b       ldr     r3, [r0, #0x38]
000314ea  d3f8ac31   ldr     r3, [r3, #0x1ac]
